==Abstract==

This BIP defines the '''Mnemonic Descriptor''' (MD) format: an encoding for bitcoin wallet policies that is compact, error-correcting, and designed for hand-transcription onto durable media (paper, steel). Where BIP 39 standardizes the mnemonic encoding of HD seed entropy, MD standardizes the analogous encoding for the ''wallet structure'' — the BIP 388 wallet policy template, derivation paths, and (when needed) foreign extended public keys — such that the structural information necessary to reconstruct a wallet can survive independently of any digital archive.

The format consists of three layers: (a) a compact bytecode for BIP 380 output descriptors and BIP 388 wallet policies, extending the tag-based encoding pioneered by the public-domain <code>descriptor-codec</code> project; (b) a codex32-derived (BIP 93) encoding layer that reuses the bech32 alphabet and BCH error-correction polynomials but introduces a new human-readable part, header structure, and multi-string chunking for arbitrary-length payloads; and (c) BCH substitution-error correction over each string (up to 4 character substitutions), with an OPTIONAL structure-guided recovery flow (future work) for damage beyond the BCH substitution limit.

==Motivation==

Bitcoin self-custody best practices require backing up the keys that control a wallet's funds. For wallets that use single-key or standard-path structures, BIP 39 provides a robust mnemonic backup: a 12- or 24-word phrase, typically engraved on metal, from which keys can be deterministically reconstructed when paired with the assumed standard derivation path.

This works for "vanilla" wallets, where the wallet structure (single-sig, BIP 44/49/84/86 path) is essentially conventional. For wallets with arbitrary spending policies expressed in miniscript — multisig, timelocks, decaying conditions, inheritance schemes — the policy structure itself becomes essential information that must be backed up, and the seed alone is insufficient. BIP 388 makes this explicit: a wallet policy that is not commonly understood "must be backed up alongside the seed... the recovery of the wallet would not be possible without it."

Existing approaches to policy backup are inadequate for the durable, engravable, decades-of-storage use case that BIP 39 mnemonics solve for seeds:

* '''JSON exports''' (Sparrow, Specter): not engravable; opaque to humans; verbose
* '''Encrypted descriptor files''' (Liana <code>.bed</code> format): not engravable; require digital infrastructure and the encryption password to decode; not human-readable
* '''Multisig configuration files''' (Coldcard, others): plaintext but several hundred bytes; multisig-only; no error correction
* '''Output descriptor strings''' (BIP 380 plain text): long; only a hash-based checksum suffix; not designed for hand transcription; embedding raw xpubs makes engraving impractical
* '''Bytewords / UR''' (Blockchain Commons): word-encoded and supports descriptors, but only CRC32 error detection (no correction); designed for QR transmission rather than engraved metal

What is missing is a format with the same robustness profile as BIP 39 — engravable, hand-transcribable, error-correcting, easily verified — but for ''wallet structure'' rather than seed entropy. This BIP defines that format.

MD is intentionally not a key-backup format. Seed phrases (BIP 39, SLIP 39) and codex32 (BIP 93) handle key material. MD handles the complementary problem: the policy template that connects keys into a wallet.

==Definitions and notation==

The key words "MUST", "MUST NOT", "REQUIRED", "SHALL", "SHALL NOT", "SHOULD", "SHOULD NOT", "RECOMMENDED", "MAY", and "OPTIONAL" in this document are to be interpreted as described in [https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc2119 RFC 2119].

The following terms are used throughout this document:

* '''Wallet policy''' — a BIP 388 wallet policy: a wallet descriptor template plus an ordered key information vector.
* '''Template''' — the BIP 388 wallet descriptor template: a script structure containing <code>@i</code> placeholders in place of keys, with each placeholder followed by a derivation path expression.
* '''Placeholder''' (<code>@i</code>) — a numeric reference (e.g., <code>@0</code>, <code>@1</code>) inside a template that resolves to a specific key information entry.
* '''Key information''' — a serialized BIP 32 extended public key (xpub) prefixed with origin information of the form <code>[fingerprint/path]xpub</code>, as defined in BIP 388.
* '''Foreign xpub''' — an xpub belonging to the policy that is ''not'' derivable from any seed the user holds (typically a cosigner's key).
* '''Owned seed''' — a BIP 39, SLIP 39, codex32, or other seed for which the user has the recovery material.
* '''Template Card''' — an MD-encoded backup of a wallet's template, derivation paths, and (optionally) master fingerprints. Always required.
* '''Xpub Card''' — an MD-encoded backup of one foreign xpub with its origin information. Required only when the policy contains foreign xpubs (the standalone Xpub Card type is deferred to v1+).
* '''Codex32''' — the BIP 93 encoding for hand-transcribed bitcoin secrets. MD reuses codex32's bech32 alphabet and BCH polynomials.
* '''bech32 alphabet''' — the 32-character set defined in BIP 173: <code>qpzry9x8gf2tvdw0s3jn54khce6mua7l</code>.
* '''Canonical bytecode''' — the deterministic byte sequence produced by encoding a given wallet policy under the MD bytecode rules. Round-trip identity: <code>decode(encode(policy)) == policy</code> in canonical form. Uniqueness is a consequence of the canonicalization rules stated normatively elsewhere in this document — ascending placeholder-index renumbering (§"Round-trip canonical form"), minimal-length LP4-ext varints (§"LP4-ext varint"), the shared-vs-divergent origin-path mode selection (§"Origin path declaration"), and ascending-tag ordering of TLV entries including preserved unknown TLVs (§"TLV section") — not an independent axiom.
* '''Chunk''' — one of one or more codex32-derived strings that together encode a single Template Card.

Bytes are written in hexadecimal as <code>0xNN</code>. Byte sequences are concatenated left-to-right in the order written. The bytecode layer is a packed bit stream (see §"Bytecode layer / General structure"); fixed-width bit fields are MSB-first, and variable-length integer fields use the LP4-ext varint encoding defined in §"LP4-ext varint". All character positions in encoded strings are 0-indexed.

==Format overview==

An MD backup of a wallet consists of one or more cards, where each card is a string of bech32 characters that can be engraved, transcribed, or otherwise stored on durable media. There are three card types:

# '''Template Card''' (this BIP, v0): encodes the wallet's template, derivation paths, and optional master fingerprints. Always required. May span one or more chunks.
# '''Xpub Card''' (deferred to v1+): encodes one foreign xpub with origin information. One per foreign xpub. Not specified in v0.
# '''Policy ID''' (optional): a short identifier derived from the wallet policy (the <code>WalletPolicyId</code>; see §"Policy identifier"), used for cross-verifying digital copies of the policy against the engraved Template Card. May be stamped separately.

The v0.30 specification scope (this document) covers wallets where the user holds every seed referenced by the policy. Per-<code>@i</code> derivation-path divergence — distinct origin and/or use-site paths per placeholder — '''is''' supported via the divergent-paths header flag (§"Origin path declaration") and the per-<code>@N</code> override TLVs, and on-card cosigner/foreign xpubs '''are''' supported via the TLV section (tags 0x00–0x03; carrying an xpub promotes the card to BIP 388 wallet-policy mode). Only the standalone '''Xpub Card''' type — a separate card encoding one foreign xpub with its own origin, one per xpub — remains deferred to a future version. Wallets meeting these criteria require only a Template Card.

''See §"Top-level descriptor scope" for the normative allow-list and §"Frequently Asked Questions" for design choices.''

Forward compatibility is preserved: MD v0 readers MUST reject backups marked with newer version bytes (loud failure), and MD v1+ readers MUST accept v0 Template Cards (graceful upgrade).

==Top-level descriptor scope==

MD is a recovery-first format: its decoder accepts the full BIP 388 top-level
surface so that any card a user may have engraved can be read back (see
"Permissive decode" below). The primary, modern top-level descriptor templates
— the shapes MD is designed around, and for which encoders emit no advisory —
are:

* '''<code>wpkh(KEY)</code>''' — BIP 84 native-segwit single-sig.
* '''<code>wsh(SCRIPT)</code>''' — native-segwit script (multisig and miniscript
  script trees per BIP 388 wallet-policy grammar).
* '''<code>sh(wpkh(KEY))</code>''' — BIP 49 nested-segwit single-sig.
* '''<code>sh(wsh(SCRIPT))</code>''' — BIP 48/1' nested-segwit multisig. The
  inner SCRIPT is subject to the same constraints as a top-level <code>wsh</code>.
* '''<code>tr(KEY)</code>''' or '''<code>tr(KEY, TREE)</code>''' — BIP 86
  taproot: keypath-only, single-leaf, or multi-leaf script tree. <code>TREE</code>
  may be a single tap-leaf script or a recursively nested script tree using the
  <code>TapTree (0x05)</code> inner-node tag, subject to BIP 341's
  <code>TAPROOT_CONTROL_MAX_NODE_COUNT = 128</code> depth ceiling. See
  §"Taproot tree" for the bytecode form. Active (v0.5).

Decoders MAY derive addresses for any of the above accepted shapes by
translating the wire AST to a BIP-380 descriptor and delegating script-
and address-construction to a BIP-380 implementation
(e.g. <code>rust-miniscript</code>'s <code>Descriptor::at_derivation_index</code>
+ <code>Descriptor::address</code>). The reference implementation
(<code>md-codec</code>) follows this approach as of v0.32; the wire format
does not itself prescribe an address-derivation algorithm beyond the
BIP-380/BIP-388 semantics inherited via the AST encoding.

MD additionally decodes the remaining BIP-388-permitted top-level forms, so a
recovery tool can read any legitimately-engraved card:

* '''<code>pkh(KEY)</code>''' — legacy P2PKH single-sig. Fully supported: it is
  the BIP 44 default and ships in the reference test corpus (<code>pkh_basic</code>).
* '''<code>sh(multi(K, ...))</code>''', '''<code>sh(sortedmulti(K, ...))</code>''',
  '''<code>sh(KEY)</code>''' — legacy P2SH. Decoded for recovery; the encoder
  emits an advisory (see "Encode-time advisory" below).

The only genuinely-rejected top-level form is:

* '''<code>bare(SCRIPT)</code>''' — pre-2014 raw script (no address; BIP 388 also
  excludes it). It has no allocated top-level tag; the reference encoder rejects
  it at the parse layer.

=====Permissive decode=====

A conformant decoder's root-tag allow-list is
<code>{sh, wsh, wpkh, pkh, tr}</code>. A wire whose root tag is outside this set
is rejected with <code>Error::OperatorContextViolation { context: TopLevel }</code>.
Inside a top-level <code>sh(...)</code>, the decoder does '''not''' peek-and-reject
the inner tag: <code>sh</code> may wrap <code>wpkh</code> (BIP 49 nested-segwit
single-sig), <code>wsh</code> (BIP 48/1' nested-segwit multisig), or a legacy
<code>multi</code>/<code>sortedmulti</code> body (legacy P2SH multisig) — all
decode. This is a deliberate recovery-safety choice: refusing to decode a
legacy form would strand funds for a user who engraved it. Reserved-tag values
(<code>Error::TagOutOfRange</code>), forbidden tap-leaf tags
(<code>Error::ForbiddenTapTreeLeaf</code>, §"Taproot tree"), and over-depth
recursion (<code>Error::DecodeRecursionDepthExceeded</code>) are still rejected;
each rejection is distinguishable from generic checksum failure and from generic
bytecode-parse failure so conformance suites can pin the error path.

=====Encode-time advisory=====

Because MD decodes the legacy forms, the safety signal moves to encode time.
Encoders SHOULD emit a warn-only advisory to stderr when asked to encode a
top-level legacy P2SH multisig (<code>sh(multi(...))</code> or
<code>sh(sortedmulti(...))</code>): third-party txid malleability, the ~520-byte
redeemScript ceiling, no witness discount, and the address-prefix footgun
described in §"Frequently Asked Questions: Why does MD warn on legacy P2SH
multisig?". The advisory does not change the card: stdout still carries the
encoded string. <code>pkh</code> and all modern forms
(<code>wpkh</code>/<code>wsh</code>/<code>tr</code>/<code>sh(wpkh)</code>/<code>sh(wsh)</code>)
encode silently.

All accepted forms follow the existing canonical form rules (no whitespace,
<code>/**</code> expansion, ascending placeholder order, <code>'</code> for
hardened). No type-specific canonicalization.

===Sh wrapper inner shapes===

When a decoder consumes a top-level <code>sh</code> bytecode tag
(primary code <code>0x03</code>), the inner bytecode tag classifies the
descriptor:

{| class="wikitable"
|+ Tag values are 6-bit primary codes per the v0.30 bytecode wire format (see §"Tag table").
! Inner tag !! Inner type !! Classification
|-
| <code>0x00</code> || <code>wpkh</code> || BIP 49 nested-segwit single-sig
|-
| <code>0x02</code> || <code>wsh</code> || BIP 48/1' nested-segwit multisig
|-
| <code>0x06</code>/<code>0x07</code> || <code>multi</code>/<code>sortedmulti</code> || legacy P2SH multisig (encode-time advisory per §"Top-level descriptor scope")
|-
| Any other || any other || decoded structurally; classified per the inner operator
|}

The reference decoder does not gate the inner tag: every <code>sh(...)</code>
shape that parses is decoded (permissive decode, §"Top-level descriptor scope").
Hostile deeply-nested inputs (e.g., <code>sh(sh(sh(...)))</code> of arbitrary
depth) are bounded not by an sh-specific peek but by the general recursion
depth gate, which rejects trees exceeding
<code>MAX_DECODE_DEPTH = 128</code> with
<code>Error::DecodeRecursionDepthExceeded</code> (§"Taproot tree").

===Elided origins and canonical-default paths===

When an origin path is not supplied explicitly, an encoder MAY '''elide''' it by
writing a depth-0 origin (the 4-bit zero-depth field of §"origin-path-encoding").
A depth-0 origin does '''not''' mean "derive at the master node <code>m</code>":
it is a signal to resolve the derivation path from the ''canonical-origin table''
keyed on the top-level wrapper shape.

{| class="wikitable"
! Wrapper shape !! Canonical origin !! Reference
|-
| <code>pkh(@N)</code> single-key || <code>m/44'/0'/0'</code> || BIP 44 (P2PKH)
|-
| <code>wpkh(@N)</code> single-key || <code>m/84'/0'/0'</code> || BIP 84 (P2WPKH)
|-
| <code>sh(wpkh(@N))</code> single-key || <code>m/49'/0'/0'</code> || BIP 49 (P2SH-P2WPKH)
|-
| <code>tr(@N)</code> key-path only (no TapTree) || <code>m/86'/0'/0'</code> || BIP 86 (P2TR)
|-
| <code>wsh(multi(...))</code> / <code>wsh(sortedmulti(...))</code> || <code>m/48'/0'/0'/2'</code> || BIP 48 P2WSH
|-
| <code>sh(wsh(multi(...)))</code> / <code>sh(wsh(sortedmulti(...)))</code> || <code>m/48'/0'/0'/1'</code> || BIP 48 P2SH-P2WSH
|}

This table reproduces the reference implementation's canonical-origin map
(<code>crates/md-codec/src/canonical_origin.rs</code>), which is the single source
of truth. '''A decoder MUST resolve a depth-0 origin, on any wrapper shape listed
in this table, through the corresponding canonical origin before deriving keys.'''
Deriving at the literal master node instead would recover the wrong wallet. Most
of the reference test corpus — and hence this BIP's §"Test Vectors" table —
carries an elided (depth-0) origin resolved this way.

An '''explicit''' origin — a non-zero-depth path written out via the
depth-prefixed §"origin-path-encoding" — is equally legal, and for a wrapper in
the table MUST resolve to the same keys as the elided form. Encoders MAY emit
either form; a change of origin (e.g. a different account index) is written
explicitly. A per-<code>@N</code> origin that differs from the wrapper default is
carried in the <code>OriginPathOverrides</code> TLV (tag <code>0x03</code>,
§"TLV section").

'''Shapes with no canonical entry.''' A top-level shape with no row in the table
above — <code>tr</code> with a script tree, legacy <code>sh(sortedmulti)</code> /
<code>sh(multi)</code>, a bare <code>wsh(@N)</code> / <code>sh(@N)</code>, or an
arbitrary miniscript body — cannot resolve a depth-0 (elided) origin from the
table. Pathless / non-canonical backup handling for these shapes is under
separate design; the current reference decoder rejects an elided origin on such a
wrapper with <code>Error::MissingExplicitOrigin { idx }</code>, requiring an
explicit origin for every <code>@N</code> (supplied via the origin path
declaration or an <code>OriginPathOverrides</code> entry).

==Specification==

===Encoding layer===

A single MD string is structured as:

<pre>
  <HRP> <separator> <header> <payload> <checksum>
</pre>

Each component is described below.

====Human-readable part====

The HRP is the two-character string <code>md</code> (lowercase) or <code>MD</code> (uppercase). HRP case MUST match the case of the data part. Mixed case within a single string is invalid and MUST be rejected.

Note: The chosen HRP is subject to formal SLIP-0173 registration (see FOLLOWUPS entry <code>slip-0173-register-md-hrp</code>). It was collision-vetted prior to adoption (see §"Why a new HRP?"). Implementations MUST use <code>md</code> until otherwise specified.

====Separator====

The separator is the single character <code>1</code>, following BIP 173 bech32 convention. The separator is excluded from the bech32 data alphabet and unambiguously marks the boundary between HRP and data.

====Header====

Each MD card's data part begins with a header that identifies the card mode, version, and (for chunked cards) reassembly information. The header is bit-packed at the front of the data part. Single-payload and chunked layouts are discriminated '''in-band''': decoders auto-dispatch on bit 0 of the first 5-bit symbol (the <code>chunked</code> flag), with no caller hint. Single-payload headers carry <code>chunked = 0</code>; chunk headers carry <code>chunked = 1</code>. See §"Auto-dispatch and v0.x rejection" below for the discrimination trace.

For '''single-string Template Cards''' (the common case for small wallets), the header is 5 bits (one bech32 character) and matches the bytecode-layer payload header described in §"Bytecode header":

* Bit 4: divergent-paths flag.
* Bits 3–0: version (v0.30 = <code>0b0100</code> = 4). The 4-bit field absorbs the bit that v0.x reserved.

For '''chunked Template Cards''', the header is 37 bits. It is '''contiguous''' with the fragment that follows: the header does not pad up to a symbol boundary, so bits 37–39 of the eighth 5-bit symbol are already the first fragment bits (see §"Chunk fragment"). The 37 header bits are:

* Bits 36–33: version (v0.30 = <code>0b0100</code>). 4-bit field.
* Bit 32: chunked flag, MUST be <code>1</code>. This is the bit-0 discriminator of the first 5-bit symbol; auto-dispatch sees it before any other field.
* Bits 31–12: chunk-set identifier (CSI), 20 bits. A deterministic per-encoding identifier shared by all chunks of one Template Card, derived from the encoding's <code>Md1EncodingId</code> (defined immediately below). Used to detect chunks from different Template Cards being mixed during reassembly.
* Bits 11–6: total chunk count, 6 bits, encoded as <code>count − 1</code>. Range <code>1..64</code>. The count is fixed by the normative sizing formula in §"Chunking" (<code>count = ⌈padded_payload_bits / 320⌉</code>); encoders MUST NOT vary it.
* Bits 5–0: chunk index, 6 bits, 0-indexed. Range <code>0..(count − 1)</code>.

The chunk-set identifier is normatively bound to the canonical encoding. Define <code>Md1EncodingId</code> as the leading 16 bytes of <code>SHA-256</code> over the canonical bit-packed payload bytecode of the Template Card — the bytecode produced by the encoder for the assembled (single-string-equivalent) payload (see §"Payload" and §"Bytecode layer"). Encoders MUST derive <code>chunk_set_id</code> from <code>Md1EncodingId</code> by taking the leading 20 bits, MSB-first:

<pre>
  chunk_set_id = (Md1EncodingId[0] << 12) | (Md1EncodingId[1] << 4) | (Md1EncodingId[2] >> 4)
</pre>

This deterministic binding makes md1 encoding bit-reproducible — any two conforming encoders given the same canonical bytecode produce identical Template Card strings — and lets downstream toolchains SHA-pin regression corpora. Decoders MUST verify, after reassembly and bytecode decode, that the wire <code>chunk_set_id</code> matches the value derived from the reassembled encoding's <code>Md1EncodingId</code>; mismatch MUST be rejected with an error specifically identifying the chunk-set-id derivation check. The reference implementation surfaces this as <code>Error::ChunkSetIdMismatch { expected, derived }</code>.

<code>Md1EncodingId</code> is the hash of the '''raw bit-packed payload bytecode''' and serves solely as the chunk-set-identifier source. It is a '''distinct value''' from the engraved policy anchor <code>WalletPolicyId</code> (§"Policy identifier"), which is hashed over a different, canonical-expanded wallet-policy preimage (template tree bits plus per-<code>@N</code> origin / use-site / fingerprint / xpub records — '''not''' the raw payload). The two are computed over different preimages; neither is a truncation of the other. See §"Policy identifier" for the anchor's construction.

'''Naming note:''' the field was called "wallet identifier" in MD versions ≤ 0.8.x. The v0.8 "wallet ID" → "Policy ID" rename mechanically renamed this chunk-header field to ''ChunkPolicyId'' as collateral, but on review for the sibling Mnemonic Key (MK) format that name was misleading: the chunk-header field is neither the policy anchor (§"Policy identifier") nor a per-instance identity — it identifies a chunk-set assembly and nothing more. v0.9 corrects the name to "chunk-set identifier" / <code>chunk_set_id</code>. Wire format and bit layout are unchanged across the v0.8 → v0.9 rename.

=====Auto-dispatch and safe rejection=====

Decoders dispatch between single-payload and chunked layouts by reading bit 0 of the first 5-bit symbol:

* <code>bit 0 = 0</code> → single-payload mode; the first symbol is <code>[paths (bit 4)][v3 (bit 3)][v2 (bit 2)][v1 (bit 1)][v0 (bit 0)]</code> — bit 4 is the divergent-<code>paths</code> flag, bits 3..1 are the version's high bits (v3, v2, v1), and bit 0 is the version's low bit <code>v0 = 0</code>.
* <code>bit 0 = 1</code> → chunked mode; treat bits 4..1 as the 4-bit version field, consume 32 more bits as chunk-header continuation.

The 4-bit version field has 16 representable values but the auto-dispatch constrains the usable subset: redesigned wire-format versions MUST have <code>v0 = 0</code> (even values), because <code>v0 = 1</code> would be mis-classified as chunked. Additionally <code>version = 0</code> collides with v0.x single-payload, and <code>version = 2</code> collides with v0.x chunked (which a v0.30 decoder reads as single-payload with version=2 — see below). The usable v0.30-family WF-redesign version set is therefore '''{4, 8, 12}'''. v0.30 uses <code>version = 4</code>; future major breaks would use 8 then 12.

v0.x payloads are rejected cleanly without silent mis-decode. The auto-dispatch trace:

{| class="wikitable"
! Input !! First 5 bits !! Decoder verdict
|-
| v0.x single-payload (version=0) || <code>[paths][0][0][0][0]</code> || bit 0 = 0 → single-payload; version = 0 → <code>Error::WireVersionMismatch { got: 0 }</code>
|-
| v0.x chunked (version=0, chunked=1) || <code>[0][0][0][1][0]</code> || bit 0 = 0 → single-payload; version = 2 → <code>Error::WireVersionMismatch { got: 2 }</code>
|-
| v0.30 single-payload || <code>[paths][0][1][0][0]</code> || bit 0 = 0 → single-payload; version = 4 → accepted
|-
| v0.30 chunked || <code>[0][1][0][0][1]</code> || bit 0 = 1 → chunked; version = 4 → accepted
|-
| v0.30 chunked read WITHOUT dispatch (non-conforming decoder routes it through the single-payload header) || <code>[0][1][0][0][1]</code> || bits 3–0 read as a single-payload version = <code>1001</code> = 9 → <code>Error::WireVersionMismatch { got: 9 }</code> — the misleading mis-parse that auto-dispatch prevents
|}

In-band auto-dispatch is '''normative''' (Decoder requirements #3, §"Decoder requirements"): a conformant decoder MUST read bit 0 of the first 5-bit symbol before interpreting any other field, and dispatch single-payload vs chunked on it — never by caller role. A decoder that skips this step and feeds a chunked string to the single-payload header path surfaces the misleading <code>got 9</code> error in the last row above. The reference <code>md decode</code> performs the bit-0 dispatch and reads single-string and chunked cards through the same entry point.

====Payload====

The payload is the canonical bit-packed bytecode (defined in §"Bytecode layer", below) of the Template Card, encoded directly as 5-bit codex32 symbols. For chunked Template Cards, each chunk's payload is a fragment of the assembled bytecode: the assembled payload is byte-padded (zero-padded to a whole-byte boundary) and split into '''whole-byte''' fragments, one per chunk. See §"Chunking" for the byte-aligned framing.

The bytecode is bit-packed (MSB-first); 5-bit symbols are emitted directly from the bit stream with no intermediate byte-aligned conversion. The final symbol may carry up to 4 bits of trailing zero padding to align the bit count with the codex32 symbol grid.

Decoders MUST reject an MD card whose '''assembled bytecode stream''' carries non-zero trailing padding bits. Because the bytecode is bit-packed and the codex32 layer emits 5-bit symbols, a conforming encoder leaves up to 7 trailing bits of '''zero''' padding after the last bytecode field (≤4 bits from the 5-bit symbol grid, plus the byte-boundary pad), tolerated at the TLV-section boundary via the rollback-as-padding mechanism (§"TLV section / End-of-section detection"). Those ≤7 rollback bits MUST be zero: a conforming encoder never emits non-zero padding, so a decoder MUST reject an assembled stream whose trailing rollback bits are non-zero rather than silently accept it. The reference implementation surfaces this rejection as <code>Error::&lt;PAD_ERROR_VARIANT_TBD_P2&gt;</code> — the exact variant name is finalized in the implementation phase — and cross-implementations MUST surface a semantically equivalent rejection, distinguishable from generic checksum failure and from generic bytecode-parse failure, so conformance tests can pin the error path. (This check applies to the '''reassembled''' bytecode stream. The ≤4 bits of per-chunk symbol-alignment padding that each chunked string carries after its fragment are discarded during reassembly (§"Reassembly") and are not conformance-checked; a conforming encoder emits them as zero.)

====Checksum====

The checksum is computed using a BCH error-correcting code with HRP-mixing applied in the BIP 173 style. The polymod algorithm is BIP 93's <code>ms32_polymod</code>, applied to the concatenation of:

# The HRP-expansion of <code>"md"</code>, computed exactly as in BIP 173 §"Bech32": for each HRP character <code>c</code> emit <code>ord(c) >> 5</code>; emit a single zero; for each HRP character emit <code>ord(c) & 31</code>. For the lowercase HRP <code>"md"</code> this yields the five 5-bit values <code>[3, 3, 0, 13, 4]</code> (length = 2 × len(HRP) + 1 = 5). Derivation: <code>ord('m') = 109 = 0x6d; 109 >> 5 = 3; 109 & 31 = 13</code>. <code>ord('d') = 100 = 0x64; 100 >> 5 = 3; 100 & 31 = 4</code>. The separator zero falls between the high-half list <code>[3, 3]</code> and the low-half list <code>[13, 4]</code>.
# The data part: header + payload as a sequence of 5-bit values from the bech32 alphabet.
# A pad of 13 zero values during encoding, or the actual 13-symbol checksum during verification.

An MD string is valid when <code>polymod(input) == T_REGULAR</code>:

* '''Regular code''' (BCH(93,80,8)): the only MD code. Checksum length is 13 symbols. <code>T_REGULAR = 0x0815c07747a3392e7</code> (65 bits).

The 93-symbol length is a bound on the '''data part''' — header + payload + the 13-symbol checksum — and '''excludes''' the 3-character HRP-plus-separator prefix, matching BIP 93's data-part accounting. A single string therefore carries at most 80 data symbols (400 payload bits) plus the 13-symbol checksum: a 93-symbol codeword. Payloads exceeding 400 bits MUST be chunked (§"Chunking"); MD has no long code (its removal from the v0.x line is recorded in §"Backwards Compatibility"). The derivation of <code>T_REGULAR</code> is documented in §"Why new target constants?" below.

====Error-correction guarantees====

The regular code (BCH(93,80,8)) guarantees, per single string:

* Detection of any error pattern affecting up to 8 characters.
* '''Correction of up to 4 character substitutions''' (normative; implemented by the reference decoder).

Detection of error patterns affecting more than 8 characters is probabilistic. The expected probability that a randomly damaged string of more than 8 errors decodes to a valid codeword is bounded by approximately 2<sup>−65</sup>.

The code's minimum distance also admits erasure decoding — up to 8 known-position erasures, and longer contiguous bursts (a cyclic <code>n−k</code>-parity argument) — but '''erasure-aware decoding is not implemented by the reference decoder''', which performs substitution-error correction only. Erasure decoding is described in this document as future work (see §"Guided recovery" and FOLLOWUP <code>impl-bch-erasure-decoding-md-mk</code>); the erasure counts above are theoretical properties of the code, not a claim about the current implementation.

Decoders SHOULD report which correction was applied (clean / N substitutions corrected / failed) per §"Decoder reporting".

Substitution correction SHOULD use Berlekamp–Massey to derive the error-locator polynomial and Forney's algorithm to derive error magnitudes, working in the field <code>GF(1024) = GF(32)[ζ] / (ζ² − ζ − P)</code> with primitive element <code>β = G·ζ</code> (order 93). The eight syndromes are computed at <code>{β<sup>77</sup>, …, β<sup>84</sup>}</code>, matching the 8-consecutive-roots window of the generator polynomial as specified in BIP 93 §"Generation of valid checksum". This canonical decoder makes the correction outputs byte-identical across implementations on the same input. Alternative algorithms (e.g., brute-force enumeration up to <code>t = 4</code>) are permitted but MAY produce different but equally-valid corrections when multiple weight-≤ 4 codewords are equidistant from the received word; the canonical decoder breaks ties by ascending position index.

====Alphabet====

The data part (header + payload + checksum) uses the bech32 alphabet:

<pre>
  qpzry9x8gf2tvdw0s3jn54khce6mua7l
</pre>

This is the same 32-character set used by BIP 173 segwit addresses, BIP 350 bech32m, and BIP 93 codex32. The alphabet excludes <code>1</code>, <code>b</code>, <code>i</code>, <code>o</code>, and uppercase variants thereof to avoid common transcription confusables.

====Length envelope====

A codex32 character is one 5-bit symbol from the bech32 alphabet. A Template Card string is the 3-character HRP-plus-separator prefix (<code>md1</code>) followed by the data part: payload symbols plus the 13-symbol BCH checksum. The 93-symbol codeword cap is on the '''data part''' and '''excludes''' the HRP prefix (BIP 93 accounting), so a single string is at most 96 characters (3 + 93).

For a single-string Template Card, the payload is the canonical bit-packed bytecode (5-bit header + origin-path-decl + use-site-path-decl + tree + TLV section), MSB-first, with up to 4 bits of trailing zero padding to align with the 5-bit codex32 symbol grid.

Maximum single-string payload: <code>(93 − 13) × 5 = 400 bits</code> (80 data symbols, ≈ 50 bytes). Payloads above 400 bits MUST be chunked.

For a chunked Template Card, each chunk's data part is the 37-bit chunk header (§"Chunk header") '''immediately followed''' by the chunk's whole-byte fragment (§"Chunk fragment"), packed contiguously into 5-bit symbols (up to 4 bits of trailing zero padding), then the 13-symbol checksum. There is no inter-field slack between the header and the fragment.

Maximum fragment per chunk: the 37-bit header plus the fragment must fit the 80-data-symbol (400-bit) regular-code budget, so at most <code>⌊(400 − 37) / 8⌋ = 45</code> whole bytes (360 bits) of fragment fit per chunk. The reference encoder uses a more conservative per-chunk budget of 320 bits (64 data symbols) to size the chunk count (§"Chunking"), leaving headroom for the 37-bit header. With up to 64 chunks, a Template Card can carry far more assembled payload than any practical wallet policy requires. The v0.30 wire format does NOT carry a separate cross-chunk hash field; cross-chunk integrity is derived from the assembled-payload SHA-256 (see §"Chunking").

===Bytecode layer===

The bytecode is the canonical compact binary encoding of a wallet policy. It is the input to the encoding layer (above) and the output of decoding.

====General structure====

The bytecode is a packed bit stream — a contiguous concatenation of variable-width bit fields with no byte alignment between sections or operators. The bit stream is laid out MSB-first into bytes; the final byte is zero-padded if the total bit count is not a multiple of 8. The trailing zero-padding is also tolerated as up to 7 bits of slack at the TLV-section boundary (see §"TLV section / end-of-section detection") because the codex32 encoding layer emits 5-bit symbols.

A single-string Template Card carries the bytecode in this order:

# Header — 5 bits.
# Origin path declaration — variable.
# Use-site path declaration — variable, always present.
# Tree — variable, recursive.
# TLV section — variable, may be empty.

For chunked Template Cards, each chunk's bit stream begins with a 37-bit chunk header (carrying the chunk-set identifier, total chunk count, and this chunk's index) instead of the 5-bit payload header. The chunked and single-string layouts have distinguishable bit prefixes (see §"Header" and §"Chunking" for the full layouts); dispatch between them is '''in-band''' — a decoder reads bit 0 of the first 5-bit symbol (the chunked flag) and dispatches on it, with no caller hint (§"Auto-dispatch and safe rejection"). After all chunks in a set are reassembled, the joined bit stream begins with the same 5-bit payload header and follows the same five-section layout above. Cross-chunk integrity is via the 20-bit chunk-set identifier carried in every chunk header (derived from the assembled payload's <code>Md1EncodingId</code>); see §"Chunking".

====Bytecode header====

The first 5 bits of the bytecode are the single-payload header:

{| class="wikitable"
! Bit !! Field !! Notes
|-
| 4 || Divergent-paths flag || <code>0</code> = a single shared origin path applies to every <code>@N</code> placeholder; <code>1</code> = one origin path per <code>@N</code> follows in the path declaration.
|-
| 3–0 || Version || 4-bit version field. v0.30 = <code>0b0100</code> (= 4). The 4-bit width absorbs the bit that v0.x reserved. Bit 0 doubles as the auto-dispatch discriminator (must be <code>0</code> for single-payload; see §"Auto-dispatch and safe rejection"). Decoders MUST reject any other value with <code>Error::WireVersionMismatch { got }</code>; the future-usable WF-redesign set is <code>{4, 8, 12}</code> per the auto-dispatch constraint.
|}

The header occupies the first 5 bits of the bit stream MSB-first; the origin path declaration begins immediately at bit 5 with no padding.

====Origin path declaration====

The origin path declaration encodes the BIP 32 derivation path(s) that produce the xpubs referenced by each <code>@N</code> placeholder. The block dispatches on header bit 4:

{| class="wikitable"
! Mode !! Header bit 4 !! Wire layout
|-
| Shared || <code>0</code> || <code>[n: 5 bits, encoded n−1] [origin-path-encoding]</code>
|-
| Divergent || <code>1</code> || <code>[n: 5 bits, encoded n−1] [origin-path-encoding × n]</code>
|}

''n'' is the descriptor's key count, range <code>1..32</code> (BIP 388 placeholder cap), encoded as <code>n−1</code> in 5 bits. Out-of-range values are rejected with <code>Error::KeyCountOutOfRange { n }</code>. In divergent mode the path encodings appear in placeholder-index order: the first encoding applies to <code>@0</code>, the second to <code>@1</code>, and so on; there is no per-entry index field — position in the list IS the index.

Conforming encoders MUST examine the placeholder paths in placeholder-index order and emit shared mode (header bit 4 = 0) when all paths are equal, divergent mode (header bit 4 = 1) otherwise. This rule is a pure function of policy state; <code>encode(decode(encode(p)))</code> is bit-identical to <code>encode(p)</code>.

=====origin-path-encoding=====

Each origin-path-encoding is:

  <code>[depth: 4 bits] [component × depth]</code>

''depth'' is the number of BIP 32 derivation components in the path, held in a 4-bit field, so the wire cannot represent a depth above 15. This is therefore an '''encoder-side''' constraint: encoders MUST reject paths deeper than 15 before serialization (<code>Error::PathDepthExceeded { got, max: 15 }</code>); a decoder reading this 4-bit field can never observe an out-of-range depth. The cap is defense-in-depth — no real-world BIP path family exceeds 6 components (BIP 48 + change/index = 6); 15 leaves generous headroom.

A depth-<code>0</code> encoding (the 4-bit zero-depth field with no following components) does '''not''' denote deriving at the literal master node <code>m</code>: it marks an '''elided''' origin, resolved through the canonical-origin table for the wrapper shape (§"Elided origins and canonical-default paths"). For a wrapper with no canonical entry, a depth-0 origin is handled per that section.

The v0.30 wire format does not carry a path dictionary; a non-elided origin path is encoded via the depth-prefixed form above, and an elided origin is the depth-0 form resolved via the canonical-origin table. (Historical context: pre-v0.11 versions carried a 1-byte indicator that selected between well-known BIP 44 / 48 / 84 / 86 / 87 paths and an explicit encoding; that mechanism was retired by the v0.11 wire-format reset and has never returned.)

=====component=====

Each component is:

  <code>[hardened: 1 bit] [value: LP4-ext varint]</code>

''hardened'' is the BIP 32 hardened bit. ''value'' is the un-hardened-bit child number, encoded as an LP4-ext varint (see §"LP4-ext varint", below). Component values up to <code>2^29 − 1</code> are representable; larger values are rejected with <code>Error::VarintOverflow { value }</code>.

=====Authority precedence with MK=====

When an MD card with per-<code>@N</code> paths participates in recovery alongside one or more MK cards (xpub backups; see [https://github.com/bg002h/mnemonic-key bg002h/mnemonic-key]), MK's <code>origin_path</code> is '''authoritative''' for the xpub's derivation; MD's per-<code>@N</code> path is '''descriptive''' — the policy's expected path layout. Per-format decoders are not required to be aware of cross-format context; consistency-checking is the recovery orchestrator's responsibility, and mismatch MUST cause the orchestrator to reject the assembly. See MK's BIP §"Authority precedence (MK ↔ MD path information)" for the full normative semantics.

====Use-site path declaration====

Following the origin path declaration is a use-site path declaration that encodes the BIP 388 multipath suffix (e.g. <code>/<0;1>/*</code>) shared by every <code>@N</code> placeholder. It is always present; its minimal form (no multipath, unhardened wildcard) is 2 bits.

  <code>[has-multipath: 1 bit]</code>
  <code>[if has-multipath:</code>
  <code>  [alt-count: 3 bits, encoded count−2; range 2..9]</code>
  <code>  [alternative × count]</code>
  <code>]</code>
  <code>[wildcard-hardened: 1 bit]</code>

''has-multipath'' is <code>1</code> if a parenthesized alternation (<code><a;b;...></code>) precedes the wildcard, <code>0</code> otherwise. ''alt-count'' is the number of alternatives, encoded as <code>count − 2</code> in 3 bits; permitted range is <code>2..9</code> (out-of-range rejected with <code>Error::AltCountOutOfRange { got }</code>). ''wildcard-hardened'' is <code>1</code> if the trailing wildcard is <code>*h</code>, <code>0</code> for <code>*</code>.

=====alternative=====

Each alternative is encoded the same way as a derivation-path component (§"component", above):

  <code>[hardened: 1 bit] [value: LP4-ext varint]</code>

The standard BIP 388 multipath form <code>/<0;1>/*</code> encodes as 16 bits: 1 (multipath present) + 3 (count = 2) + 5 (alt 0: unhardened, value 0) + 6 (alt 1: unhardened, value 1) + 1 (unhardened wildcard).

When a wallet policy needs different multipath suffixes per <code>@N</code>, the shared default declared here is overridden per placeholder by the <code>UseSitePathOverrides</code> TLV entry (see §"TLV section", below).

====Tree operators====

The wallet's script is encoded as a tree of operators. Each bytecode-layer operator is identified by a tag drawn from a '''6-bit primary code space''' (values <code>0x00</code>–<code>0x3F</code>); primary value <code>0x3F</code> is the extension prefix, in which case the next 4 bits carry an extension subcode (0x0–0xF). Primary values <code>0x24</code>–<code>0x3E</code> are reserved for future operator allocations within the semantic ranges of §"Tag table" below. The TLV section is a separate tag space at 5-bit width (see §"TLV tag allocations"); bytecode 6-bit and TLV 5-bit are distinct namespaces. The tag table below reflects the v0.30 wire format. The authoritative source is <code>crates/md-codec/src/tag.rs</code> in the reference implementation; the BIP table mirrors that mapping.

The wire format packs operator tags + their operand bits contiguously without byte alignment between operators (see §"General structure" above for the section ordering and §"Origin path declaration", §"Use-site path declaration", and §"TLV section" for the bit-aligned mechanisms that carry path-decl framing, per-<code>@N</code> origin-path overrides, fingerprints, and xpubs — none of which occupy slots in the operator-tag table below).

=====Tag table=====

Bytecode primary codes occupy a 6-bit space (values <code>0x00</code>–<code>0x3F</code>). Slots <code>0x00</code>–<code>0x23</code> are allocated to the 36 operators below; slots <code>0x24</code>–<code>0x3E</code> are reserved (decoder MUST reject with <code>Error::TagOutOfRange { primary }</code>); slot <code>0x3F</code> is the extension prefix followed by a 4-bit subcode (no extension subcodes are allocated in v0.30 — the entire 16-slot subspace is reserved).

