''Historical note.'' Pre-v0.11 wire formats carried byte-aligned framing tags <code>Placeholder = 0x33</code>, <code>SharedPath = 0x34</code>, <code>Fingerprints = 0x35</code>, and <code>OriginPaths = 0x36</code> in an 8-bit operator-tag namespace. v0.11 retired all four: path-decl framing moved into the bit-aligned §"Origin path declaration"; key references moved into inline <code>key_index</code> bit fields (§"Key references"); fingerprints, xpubs, and per-<code>@N</code> overrides moved into the §"TLV section". v0.30 retains that split and additionally widens the bytecode primary tag space from 5-bit to 6-bit, promoting 5 operators (Hash256, Ripemd160, RawPkH, False, True) from the v0.x extension subspace to direct primary slots <code>0x1F</code>–<code>0x23</code> for 4-bit-per-occurrence savings.

=====<code>tr()</code> NUMS encoding=====

In <code>tr()</code> (primary tag <code>0x01</code>), the operator body carries a 1-bit <code>is_nums</code> flag at the leading position. When <code>is_nums = 1</code>, the internal key is the BIP-341 §"Constructing and spending Taproot outputs" NUMS H-point — the x-only public key with no known discrete log:

  <code>50929b74c1a04954b78b4b6035e97a5e078a5a0f28ec96d547bfee9ace803ac0</code>

The wire shape is:

  <code>Tag::Tr(6) | is_nums(1) | [key_index(kiw) iff !is_nums] | has_tree(1) | [tree iff has_tree]</code>

When <code>is_nums = 1</code>, <code>key_index</code> is suppressed on the wire entirely (no kiw-bit field follows). When <code>is_nums = 0</code>, a <code>key_index</code> field of width <code>kiw = ⌈log₂(n)⌉</code> follows; values <code>0..n−1</code> reference <code>@i</code> placeholders. Values <code>≥ n</code> are rejected with <code>Error::NUMSSentinelConflict</code> (the field name is historical; the rejection fires for <code>is_nums = 0 ∧ key_index ≥ n</code>).

'''Canonicalization invariant.''' Encoders MUST emit <code>is_nums = 1</code> iff the descriptor's <code>tr()</code> internal key is exactly the BIP-341 NUMS H-point above. Encoders MUST emit <code>is_nums = 0</code> with <code>key_index = i</code> (where <code>0 ≤ i < n</code>) for any <code>@i</code> placeholder internal key.

'''Use cases.''' (1) Threshold/multi-key script-path-only multisig where no single key dominates (e.g. <code>thresh(2,pk(@0),pk(@1),pk(@2))</code> compiles to <code>tr(NUMS, multi_a(2,@0,@1,@2))</code>). (2) Conjunction policies where extraction fails (<code>and(pk(@0),pk(@1))</code> compiles to <code>tr(NUMS, and_v(v:pk(@0),pk(@1)))</code>). (3) Caller-explicit script-path-only spending where key-path extraction is intentionally disabled.

'''History.''' v0.17.0 carried a separate <code>Tag::TrUnspendable</code> at primary <code>0x1F</code> + ext-sub-code <code>0x05</code>; v0.18 retired that tag in favor of a sentinel <code>key_index = n</code> in a widened-by-one kiw field; v0.30 retires the sentinel in favor of the explicit <code>is_nums</code> flag here, which restores the un-widened <code>kiw = ⌈log₂(n)⌉</code> formula (saving 1 bit at each <code>n ∈ {1, 2, 4, 8, 16, 32}</code>). The Bare descriptor (<code>bare(SCRIPT)</code>) has no allocated tag — the encoder rejects it at the parse layer per §"Top-level descriptor scope".

=====Operator children layout=====

For fixed-arity operators (wrappers, binary ops, <code>andor</code>, <code>TapTree</code>) child sub-trees follow the operator's body bits in fixed order specified by the miniscript fragment definition.

Variable-arity operators fork by family:

* '''Multi-family''' (<code>multi</code>, <code>sortedmulti</code>, <code>multi_a</code>, <code>sortedmulti_a</code>) — the body is <code>Tag(6) | (k−1)(5) | (n−1)(5) | n × key_index(kiw)</code>. Each "child" is a raw kiw-width placeholder index, NOT a tagged Node. The parent operator implies all children are keys, so per-child tags are elided. Decoder MUST treat the body as exactly n raw kiw-bit fields and reject any tag byte in this region with <code>Error::OperatorContextViolation { tag, context: MultiBody }</code>.
* '''Thresh''' — the body is <code>Tag(6) | (k−1)(5) | (n−1)(5) | n × Node</code>. Each child is a full recursive Node (children can be arbitrary operators including key references, hashes, timelocks, nested logical ops).

Both families encode <code>k</code> as <code>k−1</code> in a fixed 5-bit field; both encode <code>n</code> as <code>n−1</code> in a fixed 5-bit field. The fixed-5 width is bit-efficient for the realistic range <code>1 ≤ k ≤ n ≤ 32</code> per BIP 388.

=====Key references=====

Operators that emit a key (<code>wpkh</code>, <code>pkh</code>, <code>pk_k</code>, <code>pk_h</code>, <code>tr</code>) carry the placeholder reference inline in their body bits as a <code>key_index</code> field of width <code>kiw = ⌈log₂(n)⌉</code> bits, where <code>n</code> is the descriptor's key count. <code>key_index</code> values <code>0..n−1</code> reference the corresponding <code>@i</code> placeholder in the BIP 388 key information vector; values <code>≥ n</code> are rejected with <code>Error::PlaceholderIndexOutOfRange { idx, n }</code>. The reference-implementation formula is:

  <code>kiw = 32 − (n − 1).leading_zeros()</code>     // = ⌈log₂(n)⌉ for n ≥ 2, clamped to 0 at n ∈ {0, 1}

Representative widths:

{| class="wikitable"
! n !! 1 !! 2 !! 3 !! 4 !! 5–8 !! 9–16 !! 17–32
|-
! kiw
| 0 || 1 || 2 || 2 || 3 || 4 || 5
|}

At <code>n = 1</code>, kiw = 0 and the <code>key_index</code> field is zero bits wide (no wire representation). For <code>tr()</code> only, the NUMS H-point is signalled by the 1-bit <code>is_nums</code> flag preceding <code>key_index</code> (§"<code>tr()</code> NUMS encoding"); <code>is_nums = 1</code> suppresses the kiw field entirely on the wire.

For variable-arity multi-family operators (<code>multi</code>, <code>sortedmulti</code>, <code>multi_a</code>, <code>sortedmulti_a</code>), each child key slot is a <code>key_index</code> field of the same <code>kiw</code> bit width, packed contiguously after the threshold and count fields per §"Operator children layout".

Inline keys (raw xpubs, raw pubkeys) are NOT permitted in v0; every key position references a BIP 388 placeholder. This guarantees the Template Card encodes the wallet structure without carrying any key material.

====TLV section====

Following the operator tree is the TLV (tag-length-value) section, which carries optional metadata: per-<code>@N</code> use-site path overrides, master-key fingerprints, xpubs, and per-<code>@N</code> origin-path overrides. The TLV section runs from the end of the tree until the codex32 symbol-aligned bit stream is exhausted; it may be empty.

Each TLV entry is:

  <code>[tag: 5 bits] [length: LP4-ext varint, in BITS] [payload: length bits]</code>

The ''length'' field gives the payload size in '''bits''' (not bytes). Entries appear in strictly ascending tag-value order; duplicates and out-of-order entries are rejected. Unknown tags (those not allocated below) are '''preserved verbatim''': a decoder MUST buffer each unknown entry's payload bits unchanged and re-emit it on re-encode, in ascending tag-value order interleaved with the known entries. A decoder MUST NOT drop an unknown entry — dropping one changes the re-encoded bytecode and breaks the chunk-set-identifier check for any chunked card that carries a reserved-tag TLV (§"Chunking"). (This is a stricter contract than plain length-prefix skipping, which would silently discard the entry.)

=====TLV tag allocations=====

{| class="wikitable"
! Tag !! Entry !! Payload shape
|-
| <code>0x00</code> || <code>UseSitePathOverrides</code> || Sparse <code>(idx: kiw bits, use-site-path: per §"Use-site path declaration")</code> list. Overrides the shared use-site default for the listed <code>@N</code>.
|-
| <code>0x01</code> || <code>Fingerprints</code> || Sparse <code>(idx: kiw bits, fingerprint: 32 bits)</code> list. Master-key fingerprint for the listed <code>@N</code>, in BIP 32 byte order.
|-
| <code>0x02</code> || <code>Pubkeys</code> || Sparse <code>(idx: kiw bits, xpub: 520 bits)</code> list. xpub bytes are chain-code (32 bytes) followed by compressed pubkey (33 bytes). A non-empty <code>Pubkeys</code> entry promotes the descriptor to BIP 388 wallet-policy mode (xpubs are carried on the wire, not derived from origin paths).
|-
| <code>0x03</code> || <code>OriginPathOverrides</code> || Sparse <code>(idx: kiw bits, origin-path-encoding: per §"origin-path-encoding")</code> list. Overrides the canonical origin path for the listed <code>@N</code> when the wrapper origin is non-canonical or undefined.
|-
| <code>0x04</code>–<code>0x1F</code> || ''reserved'' || Reserved for future TLV allocations. Decoders MUST preserve unknown tags verbatim (buffer the payload via the length-prefix and re-emit in ascending tag order); they MUST NOT drop them.
|}

''kiw'' (key-index width) is <code>⌈log₂(n)⌉</code> per §"Key references", identical to the tree's <code>key_index</code> field width. Sparse-TLV invariants (uniform across all four sparse TLVs):

* Each <code>idx < n</code>; out-of-range rejected with <code>Error::PlaceholderIndexOutOfRange</code>.
* Indices appear in strictly ascending order; non-ascending rejected with <code>Error::OverrideOrderViolation</code>.
* Each TLV is non-empty; encoders MUST omit a TLV entry when it carries no content (no <code>(idx, value)</code> pairs).

=====Fingerprints — privacy=====

The <code>Fingerprints</code> TLV (tag <code>0x01</code>) leaks which seeds match which <code>@N</code> placeholders. It is optional metadata; implementations SHOULD NOT emit it by default. Recovery tools MUST warn the user before including fingerprints, especially for solo-user single-seed wallets where the disclosure is unnecessary. Decoders that surface parsed fingerprints to the user MUST flag the data as privacy-sensitive.

When fingerprints are absent (the default), recovery tools match seeds to placeholders by trial derivation and xpub comparison, which is computationally trivial for typical wallets.

=====End-of-section detection (rollback-as-padding)=====

The TLV section has no explicit terminator: it runs until the codex32 symbol-aligned bit stream is exhausted. Because the wire is packed into 5-bit codex32 symbols, the final symbol can introduce up to 4 bits of trailing zero-padding (and the byte boundary up to 7 bits) that are not part of any TLV entry. Decoders therefore need a precise contract for distinguishing "end of section reached" from "malformed TLV entry."

Decoders SHOULD use a save/restore-position mechanism on the bit-reader so that partial reads do not consume bits prematurely. The contract is:

# Before parsing each candidate TLV entry, save the bit-reader position.
# Attempt to read <code>[tag: 5 bits] [length: LP4-ext varint] [payload: length bits]</code> plus any per-tag inner-record validation.
# On any parse failure, restore the bit-reader to the saved position and inspect the bits remaining at that position.
# '''If <code>remaining_bits ≤ 7</code>''', inspect those bits: if '''all are zero''' they are the codex32 symbol-alignment padding and the decoder treats the failure as a clean end-of-section marker and stops; if '''any is non-zero''' the decoder MUST reject the card per §"Payload" (<code>Error::&lt;PAD_ERROR_VARIANT_TBD_P2&gt;</code>).
# '''If <code>remaining_bits > 7</code>''', the failure represents a genuinely malformed input and the original parse error is propagated.

The 7-bit padding tolerance accommodates the symbol-aligned wire's worst-case trailing slack. Encoders MUST omit empty TLVs; decoders therefore treat any zero-length TLV at end-of-stream as padding via the rollback path rather than as a valid empty entry.

=====Bit-layout example=====

The bytecode for the policy <code>wsh(multi(2, @0/<0;1>/*, @1/<0;1>/*))</code> with the BIP 48 mainnet multisig P2WSH shared origin path <code>m/48'/0'/0'/2'</code> and no fingerprints is the 82-bit stream <code>2052d84212a00182182140</code> (11 bytes; 82 bits used, 6 bits trailing zero-padding from the last byte). Reproducible via the reference CLI: <code>md encode --path "m/48'/0'/0'/2'" 'wsh(multi(2,@0/<0;1>/*,@1/<0;1>/*))'</code> followed by <code>md bytecode &lt;phrase&gt;</code>. Section breakdown (n = 2, kiw = ⌈log₂(2)⌉ = 1):

