! Bits !! Section !! Decoded
|-
| 5 || Header || <code>00100</code> — paths flag <code>0</code>, version <code>0b0100</code> = 4
|-
| 5 || Path-decl: <code>n−1</code> || <code>00001</code> — <code>n = 2</code> placeholders
|-
| 4 || Path-decl: depth || <code>0100</code> — 4 components
|-
| 11 || Path-decl: comp[0] = <code>48'</code> || <code>1 0110 110000</code> — hardened, LP4(L=6), value 48 = <code>0b110000</code>
|-
| 5 || Path-decl: comp[1] = <code>0'</code> || <code>1 0000</code> — hardened, LP4(L=0), value 0
|-
| 5 || Path-decl: comp[2] = <code>0'</code> || <code>1 0000</code> — hardened, LP4(L=0), value 0
|-
| 7 || Path-decl: comp[3] = <code>2'</code> || <code>1 0010 10</code> — hardened, LP4(L=2), value 2
|-
| 16 || Use-site path: <code>/<0;1>/*</code> || <code>1 000 (0 0000) (0 0001 1) 0</code> — multipath present, count−2=0 (count=2), alt 0 = unhardened 0, alt 1 = unhardened 1, unhardened wildcard
|-
| 6 || Tree: <code>wsh</code> tag || <code>000010</code> — primary tag <code>0x02</code>
|-
| 6 || Tree: <code>multi</code> tag || <code>000110</code> — primary tag <code>0x06</code>
|-
| 5 || Tree: <code>k − 1</code> || <code>00001</code> — threshold k = 2
|-
| 5 || Tree: <code>n − 1</code> || <code>00001</code> — child count n = 2
|-
| 1 || Tree: idx[0] || <code>0</code> — placeholder <code>@0</code> (kiw = 1)
|-
| 1 || Tree: idx[1] || <code>1</code> — placeholder <code>@1</code>
|-
| 0 || TLV section || empty (no fingerprints, no overrides)
|}

Section sums: 5 (header) + 37 (path-decl: 5+4+11+5+5+7) + 16 (use-site) + 24 (tree: <code>wsh</code>(6) + <code>multi</code>(6) + <code>k−1</code>(5) + <code>n−1</code>(5) + 2 × idx(1)) + 0 (TLV) = 82 bits. Note the multi-family body packs raw kiw-bit indices directly (no per-child tags) per §"Operator children layout"; this is the key v0.30 multi-family packing change relative to v0.x's per-child <code>pk_k</code> framing.

The same policy with a <code>Fingerprints</code> TLV entry binding <code>@0</code> to <code>0xdeadbeef</code> and <code>@1</code> to <code>0xcafebabe</code> is the 164-bit stream <code>2052d84212a00182182142f09bd5b7ddfcafebabe0</code> (21 bytes; 164 bits used, 4 bits trailing zero-padding). The first 82 bits are identical to the no-fingerprints encoding above; the trailing 82 bits are the <code>Fingerprints</code> TLV entry:

{| class="wikitable"
! Bits !! Field !! Decoded
|-
| 5 || TLV tag || <code>00001</code> — tag <code>0x01</code> (<code>Fingerprints</code>)
|-
| 11 || TLV length || LP4 varint encoding 66 (= 2 entries × (kiw + 32) = 2 × 33 bits); <code>0111 1000010</code> (L=7, payload <code>1000010</code>)
|-
| 1 || Entry 0 idx || <code>0</code> — placeholder <code>@0</code> (kiw = 1)
|-
| 32 || Entry 0 fingerprint || <code>deadbeef</code>
|-
| 1 || Entry 1 idx || <code>1</code> — placeholder <code>@1</code>
|-
| 32 || Entry 1 fingerprint || <code>cafebabe</code>
|}

====LP4-ext varint====

LP4-ext is the variable-length integer encoding used for path-component values, use-site-path alternative values, and TLV-length fields. Bit-aligned, MSB-first within each field.

  <code>single-form (L < 15):    [L: 4 bits] [payload: L bits]</code>
  <code>extension-form (L = 15): [L: 4 bits = 15] [L_high: 4 bits]</code>
  <code>                         [payload_low: 14 bits] [payload_high: L_high bits]</code>
  <code>                         total = (payload_high << 14) | payload_low</code>

In single-form, ''L'' bits of payload follow the 4-bit length prefix MSB-first. In extension-form (signaled by <code>L = 15</code>), an additional 4-bit ''L_high'' selects 1..15 extra payload bits beyond the 14-bit ''payload_low''; the full value is reassembled as <code>(payload_high << 14) | payload_low</code>. Total payload capacity is up to <code>14 + 15 = 29</code> bits, encoding values <code>0..2^29 − 1</code>. Out-of-range values are rejected with <code>Error::VarintOverflow { value }</code>.

'''Canonicality.''' Encoders MUST use the minimal-length encoding for every value: the smallest <code>L</code> that fits it (single-form for values needing ≤ 14 payload bits), and extension-form only when the value needs more than 14 payload bits (with <code>L_high ≥ 1</code>). Decoders are '''lenient''': they accept a non-minimal encoding (an over-long <code>L</code>, or extension-form with <code>L_high = 0</code>) with no decode-side minimality check. Enforcing minimality on decode would flip a previously-decodable single-string wire to a reject, violating the recovery-safety invariant. A non-minimal encoding is nonetheless never silently ratified for a '''chunked''' card: reassembly re-encodes the decoded policy minimally, so a non-minimal wire produces a derived chunk-set identifier that differs from the wire value and is rejected with <code>Error::ChunkSetIdMismatch</code> (§"Chunking").

Bit costs for representative values: <code>0</code> is 4 bits (L=0, no payload); <code>1</code> is 5 bits (L=1, 1-bit payload); <code>84</code> is 11 bits (L=7, 7-bit payload); <code>16383</code> is 18 bits (L=14, 14-bit payload, single-form boundary); <code>16384</code> is 23 bits (extension-form, L_high=1).

Note: LP4-ext applies to variable-range fields only — path-component values, use-site-path alternative values, and TLV length values. The <code>multi</code>, <code>sortedmulti</code>, <code>multi_a</code>, <code>sortedmulti_a</code>, and <code>thresh</code> threshold (<code>k − 1</code>) and count (<code>n − 1</code>) fields use '''fixed 5-bit''' encoding, NOT LP4-ext: bounded by the BIP 388 wallet-policy cap of ≤ 32 keys, fixed-5 is bit-efficient for every realistic value 1..31 (saves 11 bits across the 17-wallet validation corpus relative to LP4-ext throughout). Timelock values (<code>after</code>, <code>older</code>) are encoded as raw 32-bit fields per BIP 68 / BIP 113.

====Taproot tree====

The <code>tr()</code> operator (<code>0x01</code>) encodes a top-level taproot wallet policy. The internal-key sub-tree (a key reference) immediately follows the <code>tr()</code> tag. The optional script-tree position that follows is one of:

* Absent — keypath-only <code>tr(KEY)</code>; no further bytes in the operator payload.
* A single tap-leaf miniscript — encoded directly as a leaf-script tag sequence (any operator from the per-leaf miniscript subset detailed below in this section). This is the <code>tr(KEY, leaf)</code> form.
* A <code>TapTree</code> inner-node framing — a recursive <code>[TapTree=0x05][LEFT_SUBTREE][RIGHT_SUBTREE]</code> sequence where each <code>SUBTREE</code> is recursively defined as another tap-leaf or another inner-node framing. This is the <code>tr(KEY, TREE)</code> multi-leaf form. (Historical tag-value drift: <code>TapTree</code> was 0x08 in v0.5, renumbered to 0x07 in v0.6, renumbered to 0x05 in v0.11; the v0.30 6-bit primary tag space keeps 0x05.)

Multi-leaf taproot trees are encoded recursively using the <code>TapTree (0x05)</code> tag as inner-node framing. BIP 388's curly-brace source form <code>{LEFT, RIGHT}</code> is the human-readable counterpart of this bytecode; the MD bytecode is the wire encoding of that grammar.

The decoder enforces BIP 341's <code>TAPROOT_CONTROL_MAX_NODE_COUNT = 128</code> ceiling on tree depth via a peek-before-recurse pattern: a <code>0x05</code> tag is consumed only after the depth gate passes, so a hostile producer cannot blow the parser's stack via deeply nested framings. Decoders MUST reject trees that would exceed depth 128 with <code>Error::DecodeRecursionDepthExceeded { depth, max: 128 }</code>.

Implementations MAY enforce a per-leaf miniscript subset matching their target hardware signer's documented admit list. The MD encoding format itself does not require this — see §"Signer compatibility (informational)" below for the layered-responsibility framing. Implementations SHOULD clearly document any such limitations per BIP 388 §"Implementation guidelines".

=====Signer compatibility (informational)=====

The MD encoding format is neutral on hardware-signer compatibility. An MD-encoded backup of a BIP 388 wallet policy is structurally well-formed if and only if the policy parses under BIP 388 + BIP 379; whether the policy is signable on a particular hardware signer is a separate concern handled by tools above and below MD.

The responsibility chain is:

# Wallet software (e.g., Sparrow, Liana, Specter, Bitcoin Core) constructs a BIP 388 wallet policy. The wallet should know which signer the policy targets and produce shapes the signer admits.
# MD encodes the policy losslessly into engravable steel-backup form.
# The user, recovering the backup, decodes the MD string back into a BIP 388 policy.
# The recovery wallet pairs the policy with the matching signer and constructs spending transactions.

If an MD-encoded backup contains operators a recovery-time signer will not sign, recovery may require either a different signer or manual signing infrastructure (Bitcoin Core, custom signing pipelines).

Implementations MAY provide opt-in signer-subset validators as a layered concern. Such validators are tracked separately from this specification — see for example the named subsets maintained for Coldcard (firmware/edge <code>docs/taproot.md</code>) and Ledger (<code>LedgerHQ/vanadium</code> <code>apps/bitcoin/common/src/bip388/cleartext.rs</code>). The reference implementation does not currently ship such a validator; were one added it would sit above <code>md-codec</code> as a separate layered checker, not as part of the wire format.

