For the BIP-341 NUMS H-point key-path-only form (<code>tr(NUMS, ...)</code>), the body's leading <code>is_nums</code> bit is set and the <code>key_index</code> field is suppressed entirely on the wire. The descriptor's tree omits any internal-key placeholder. See §"<code>tr()</code> NUMS encoding" above for the canonicalization invariant; concrete worked NUMS examples can be regenerated via <code>md compile --context tap '...'</code> in the reference implementation when built with the <code>cli-compiler</code> feature.

====Round-trip canonical form====

An MD-encoded Template Card MUST round-trip losslessly with the BIP 388 wallet policy string in canonical form. Canonical form requires:

* No optional whitespace anywhere in the policy string.
* Multipath shorthand <code>/**</code> is expanded to <code>/&lt;0;1&gt;/*</code> in canonical form.
* The key information vector is ordered by ascending placeholder index, with <code>@0</code> first.
* Hardened path components use the <code>'</code> character (not <code>h</code> or <code>H</code>).

Encoders MUST produce canonical form. Decoders MUST accept canonical form and SHOULD accept the equivalent non-canonical forms above (normalizing on decode). Decoders MAY reject other non-canonical inputs (e.g., re-ordered key vectors that don't match placeholder indices).

'''Walker normalization invariant.''' At every key-check position the canonical wire shape is a bare <code>Tag::PkK</code> (or <code>Tag::PkH</code>) — <code>Tag::Check</code> is NEVER emitted wrapping a key leaf. The renderer reconstructs the <code>c:</code> wrapper at output time for canonical BIP 388 rendering of <code>c:pk_k(K)</code> / <code>c:pk_h(K)</code> (or the BIP 379 sugar <code>pk(K)</code> / <code>pkh(K)</code>). <code>Tag::Check</code> remains valid on the wire only when wrapping a non-key child. This eliminates per-c:-position duplication, saving ~5 bits per key-check site.

===Chunking===

When a Template Card's canonical bytecode exceeds the single-string regular-code cap (80 data symbols = 400 payload bits, §"Length envelope"), the encoding MUST be chunked. Encoders MAY also chunk a smaller bytecode for ergonomic reasons (e.g., to fit on physical media) but SHOULD prefer single-string encoding when the payload fits; the reference <code>md encode</code> CLI requires an explicit <code>--force-chunked</code> flag to chunk a payload that would fit in a single string.

'''Chunk-count sizing and fragment split (normative — deterministic).''' The chunk count is fixed by a per-chunk budget of 320 payload bits (64 data symbols): <code>count = ⌈padded_payload_bits / 320⌉</code>, where <code>padded_payload_bits</code> is the assembled payload zero-padded to a whole byte. If <code>count > 64</code> the encoder MUST reject the payload (too large to chunk). This 320-bit budget is deliberately below the 360-bit theoretical per-chunk maximum (§"Length envelope") so the 37-bit chunk header always fits alongside the fragment inside one regular-code codeword. The assembled payload (byte length <code>plen</code>) is then split into exactly <code>count</code> whole-byte fragments with <code>bytes_per_chunk = ⌈plen / count⌉</code>: fragment <code>i</code> is the byte slice <code>[i · bytes_per_chunk, min((i+1) · bytes_per_chunk, plen))</code> — the leading fragments each carry <code>bytes_per_chunk</code> bytes and the final fragment carries the (possibly shorter) remainder. Because both the count and the split are fully determined by the assembled payload, any two conforming encoders emit '''identical''' chunk strings for the same policy.

====Chunk header (37 bits)====

Each chunk is a complete codex32-derived string. In place of the 5-bit payload header used by single-string Template Cards (§"Bytecode header"), each chunk's bit stream begins with a 37-bit chunk header. The first 5-bit symbol carries the auto-dispatch discriminator at bit 0 (<code>chunked = 1</code>); see §"Auto-dispatch and safe rejection".

{| class="wikitable"
! Bits !! Field !! Notes
|-
| 36–33 || Version || 4-bit version. v0.30 = <code>0b0100</code> (= 4). Usable WF-redesign set is <code>{4, 8, 12}</code> per §"Auto-dispatch and safe rejection".
|-
| 32 || Chunked flag || MUST be <code>1</code> in chunk headers. This is bit 0 of the first 5-bit codex32 symbol; auto-dispatch reads it before any other field. The single-payload header carries <code>chunked = 0</code> at the same bit position (which is the low bit <code>v0</code> of its version field).
|-
| 31–12 || Chunk-set identifier (CSI) || 20 bits. Derived from the assembled payload's <code>Md1EncodingId</code> (top 20 bits of <code>SHA-256</code> over the canonical bit-packed payload, MSB-first). Identical across all chunks in a set; functions as the cross-chunk integrity anchor.
|-
| 11–6 || Count − 1 || Total chunks in the set, range <code>1..64</code>, encoded as <code>count − 1</code> in 6 bits. Out-of-range rejected with <code>Error::ChunkCountOutOfRange</code>.
|-
| 5–0 || Index || This chunk's zero-based index within the set, in 6 bits. MUST be less than ''count''; out-of-range rejected with <code>Error::ChunkIndexOutOfRange</code>.
|}

====Chunk fragment====

After the 37-bit chunk header, each chunk carries a '''whole-byte fragment''' of the assembled payload. The assembled payload — the same canonical bit-packed bytecode a single string would carry, zero-padded to a whole-byte boundary — is split into <code>count</code> near-equal whole-byte slices, one per chunk; slice ''i'' is written as its bytes (8 bits each) immediately after chunk ''i'''s 37-bit header. The header/fragment boundary is exactly bit 37, '''contiguous''' (no slack): the first fragment byte's high bits share the eighth 5-bit symbol with the last header bits. The division is therefore fixed deterministically by the near-equal whole-byte split — there is no encoder-chosen bit-boundary freedom — and a decoder recovers each slice as <code>⌊(symbol-aligned-bit-count − 37) / 8⌋</code> whole bytes (the ≤4 trailing symbol-padding bits per chunk are discarded).

'''Note — do not cross-import mk1's framing.''' The sibling Mnemonic Key (MK / <code>mk1</code>) format chunks with a '''fixed 53-byte''' fragment per chunk (one xpub-sized record); md1 does '''not'''. An md1 chunk carries a variable, near-equal whole-byte slice sized from the payload and the 320-bit budget above. Implementers MUST NOT apply mk1's fixed-53-byte framing to md1 chunks.

The chunk-set identifier serves the cross-chunk integrity role that a separate appended hash served in earlier wire formats. Because the CSI is derived from the assembled-payload SHA-256, an encoder that draws a non-conforming CSI produces a string whose CSI cannot be reproduced by a conforming decoder; mismatch is detected at reassembly (see below). v0.30 does NOT carry a separate cross-chunk hash field.

====Reassembly====

Decoders reassemble a chunked Template Card by:

# Collecting all chunks transcribed by the user.
# Verifying all chunks share the same 20-bit chunk-set identifier; reject if mixed.
# Verifying all chunks declare the same total chunk count; reject if inconsistent.
# Sorting chunks by chunk index; reject if any index appears multiple times or is missing.
# Verifying the highest index equals (count − 1); reject if not.
# Concatenating each chunk's fragment '''bytes''' in index order to reconstruct the byte-padded canonical payload.
# Decoding the assembled payload as a Template Card (5-bit header at bit offset 0, then the standard five-section layout).
# Computing <code>Md1EncodingId</code> from the canonical bit-packed re-encoding of the decoded Template Card and verifying that the chunk-headers' wire chunk-set identifier matches the value derived from <code>Md1EncodingId</code> per §"Chunk header"; reject on mismatch with an error specifically identifying the derivation check (the reference implementation surfaces this as <code>Error::ChunkSetIdMismatch</code>). This ratifies that the encoder followed the deterministic-CSI contract; a non-conforming encoder that drew a random value would produce a string unreadable by conforming decoders.

===Policy identifier===

The engraved policy anchor is the '''<code>WalletPolicyId</code>''' — a 16-byte identifier that MAY be rendered as a 12-word BIP 39 phrase and stamped on a separate medium for offline cross-verification of a digital backup against the engraved Template Card. It is a canonical-expanded hash of the wallet ''policy'' — the template tree plus the per-<code>@N</code> origin / use-site / fingerprint / xpub records — so that two engravings of the same logical wallet produce the same anchor whether they elide canonical paths or write them out explicitly.

'''Preimage (byte-exact; reference: <code>crates/md-codec/src/identity.rs</code>).''' The <code>WalletPolicyId</code> is <code>SHA-256(preimage)[0..16]</code>, where <code>preimage = canonical_template_tree_bytes || concat(records)</code> is built as:

# '''Canonicalize''' placeholder indices (ascending first-occurrence renumbering) so the anchor is invariant to placeholder permutation.
# '''<code>canonical_template_tree_bytes</code>''' — write the placeholder-form tree (§"Tree operators") into a fresh bit stream and finalize (zero-pad to a whole byte). These are the tree bits ONLY — no header, no path declaration, no TLVs.
# Expand to per-<code>@N</code> records in ascending index order. For each record, resolve then serialize:
#* '''Resolve the origin path''': an explicit path verbatim, or — for an elided (depth-0) origin on a canonical wrapper — the canonical-origin table value (§"Elided origins and canonical-default paths"). This resolution is what makes the anchor stable across origin-elision.
#* '''Record bytes''': into a fresh bit stream write <code>varint(origin_path_bit_len)</code> (LP4-ext varint, length in '''bits'''), then the origin-path bits MSB-first, then <code>varint(use_site_bit_len)</code>, then the use-site-path bits; finalize (single whole-byte pad).
#* '''<code>presence_byte</code>''' <code>= (fp_present | (xpub_present << 1)) & 0b0000_0011</code> — bit 0 set iff a fingerprint is present for this <code>@N</code>, bit 1 set iff an xpub is present; bits 2–7 are reserved and MUST be 0.
#* Append <code>presence_byte || record_bytes || fingerprint? || xpub?</code>, where <code>fingerprint</code> is 4 bytes and <code>xpub</code> is the 65-byte wire form (32-byte chain code || 33-byte compressed pubkey) when present.

The anchor is therefore stable across origin- and use-site-path elision, and '''presence-significant''' on the fingerprint and xpub axes: two cards carrying the same template + paths but a different set of concrete xpubs (or fingerprints) produce different anchors, and a template-only card differs from the same wallet with concrete cosigner xpubs.

A <code>WalletPolicyId</code> is OPTIONAL and never required for recovery from the Template Card alone; it serves only as a cryptographic anchor for verifying that a supplemental digital copy of the policy is authentic.

'''Engraving — MAY, not SHOULD.''' The 12-word <code>WalletPolicyId</code> phrase (<code>WalletPolicyId::to_phrase()</code>) encodes the 16-byte (128-bit) identifier as 12 BIP 39 words — 132 bits total: the 128 identifier bits plus a 4-bit checksum. It MAY be engraved on a separate metal anchor for offline cross-verification with a digital backup. Users who maintain only the codex32 Template Card need not engrave the phrase — the codex32 string carries the policy directly with BCH error correction; the phrase is a redundant integrity check, not a recovery primitive. For a minimal-cost identifier, the top 4 bytes of the <code>WalletPolicyId</code>, rendered as 8 lowercase hex characters (parallel to a BIP 32 master-key fingerprint), are offered as a short display form; the reference CLI exposes it via <code>md encode --policy-id-fingerprint</code> and <code>md inspect</code>. (<code>WalletPolicyId</code> has no dedicated <code>fingerprint()</code> method; the short form is the first 4 bytes of its <code>as_bytes()</code>.)

The <code>WalletPolicyId</code> is a distinct value from <code>Md1EncodingId</code> (§"Header"), which hashes the '''raw bit-packed payload bytecode''' and is the chunk-set-identifier source. The reference implementation also defines a <code>WalletDescriptorTemplateId</code> (template content only — use-site-path-decl bits, tree bits, and use-site-override TLV bits — excluding the origin paths and fingerprints); it is not engraved and is out of scope for this section.

====Template-level vs instance-level identity====

The single <code>WalletPolicyId</code> anchor spans both levels of specificity because its preimage is '''presence-significant''' on the xpub axis (see the construction above):

* '''Template-level''' — a Template Card carrying no concrete xpubs (no <code>Pubkeys</code> TLV). Its <code>WalletPolicyId</code> identifies the wallet ''template + path layout'': the BIP 388 script structure plus the per-<code>@N</code> origin paths. Two wallets with the same template and path layout but different concrete cosigner xpubs share this template-level anchor.
* '''Instance-level''' — a card that also carries concrete xpubs. The 65-byte xpub bytes fold into the preimage, so the <code>WalletPolicyId</code> now distinguishes wallet ''instances'': two wallets are distinct even if they share a template and path layout, as long as their cosigner xpub sets differ.

There is '''no''' separate on-card "Wallet Instance ID" value and no separate hash domain: the per-instance identity is the same <code>WalletPolicyId</code>, computed over a preimage that includes the xpubs when they are present. The wire carries only the 65-byte (chain-code || compressed-pubkey) xpub entries of TLV <code>0x02</code>; the full 78-byte BIP 32 extended-key serialization is '''not''' reconstructible from card data (the parent fingerprint and depth are not on the wire), so any identity computation MUST use the 65-byte wire form, as the preimage above does.

'''Path-divergence injectivity.''' Two policies with the same script template but different per-cosigner origin paths (e.g. one cosigner on BIP 48 account 0' vs account 1') hash to different <code>WalletPolicyId</code>s, because the per-<code>@N</code> origin bits are part of the preimage — they are different wallet shapes. (Historical note: MD versions ≤ 0.9 lossily flattened divergent per-<code>@N</code> paths to a single shared path and so collided such wallets; the per-<code>@N</code> origin encoding of v0.10+ closed that. See §"Backwards Compatibility".)

===Decoder requirements===

Conformant MD decoders MUST:

# Recognize the MD HRP and reject any other HRP.
# Reject mixed-case strings.
# Auto-dispatch single-payload vs chunked by reading bit 0 of the first 5-bit symbol (§"Auto-dispatch and safe rejection"); reject WF-version mismatch cleanly.
# Reject reserved-range tag values and structurally-invalid operator-context positions per the error taxonomy below.
# Implement BCH substitution-error correction for the regular code per the polynomials specified above (up to 4 character substitutions).
# Verify the chunk-set identifier on reassembled chunks (compute <code>Md1EncodingId</code> from the assembled payload and reject if its top 20 bits differ from the chunk headers' wire <code>chunk_set_id</code>).
# Validate the bytecode against the tag table (reject reserved-range operator tags; preserve unknown TLV tags verbatim per §"TLV section") and enforce the decoder canonical-form validators (§"Decoder canonical-form validators").
# Reject non-zero trailing padding (§"Payload").
# Round-trip with BIP 388 canonical form.

Decoders SHOULD:

# Implement erasure-aware decoding when the user supplies known-bad positions ('''future work''' — the reference decoder performs substitution correction only; FOLLOWUP <code>impl-bch-erasure-decoding-md-mk</code>).
# Implement structure-aware candidate filtering during recovery (see §"Guided recovery"; '''future work''' — FOLLOWUP <code>impl-guided-recovery-md-mk</code>).
# Provide informational reporting on every decode attempt (§"Decoder reporting").
# Display the bech32 alphabet and example characters during user transcription.

====Error taxonomy====

Conformant decoders MUST distinguish the following structurally-defined error categories. The reference implementation surfaces each as a distinct <code>Error</code> variant in <code>crates/md-codec/src/error.rs</code>; cross-implementations MUST surface semantically equivalent categories so conformance test suites can pin error paths.

{| class="wikitable"
! Error !! Trigger
|-
| <code>WireVersionMismatch { got: u8 }</code> || Single-payload or chunked version field ≠ accepted v0.30 value (4 in this release). Per the auto-dispatch trace, v0.x payloads surface here cleanly.
|-
| <code>MalformedHeader { detail }</code> || Chunked-flag inconsistent with caller context; chunk-header fields out of range; chunk-header version mismatched with payload version.
|-
| <code>TagOutOfRange { primary: u8 }</code> || 6-bit primary in reserved range <code>0x24</code>–<code>0x3E</code>; primary <code>0x3F</code> extension prefix with any subcode (no extension subcodes allocated in v0.30).
|-
| <code>Codex32DecodeError(String)</code> || BCH verify returns false (HRP mismatch, uncorrectable transcription error, wrong format) or any other codex32-layer failure surfaced by the underlying decoder.
|-
| <code>OperatorContextViolation { tag, context: ContextKind }</code> || Tag in a forbidden position. <code>ContextKind</code> enum: <code>TopLevel</code> (e.g., bare <code>PkK</code> as top-level descriptor), <code>TapLeaf</code> (e.g., <code>Multi</code> instead of <code>MultiA</code> inside a tap leaf), <code>MultiBody</code> (non-key tag appearing where the multi-family raw kiw-bit index stream is expected). Decoder enforces the <code>TopLevel</code> check at <code>decode_payload</code>; raised when the root tag is outside the wrapper-tag allow-list <code>{Sh, Wsh, Wpkh, Pkh, Tr}</code> (since v0.31.0). <code>TapLeaf</code> is covered by the narrower <code>ForbiddenTapTreeLeaf</code> for BIP-342 leaf restrictions; <code>MultiBody</code> is structurally unreachable in v0.30+ encodings.
|-
| <code>NUMSSentinelConflict</code> || Inside <code>tr()</code> body: <code>is_nums = 0</code> with <code>key_index ≥ n</code>. (Field name is historical from the v0.18 sentinel design; v0.30 surfaces the same logical condition under the explicit-flag encoding.)
|-
| <code>DecodeRecursionDepthExceeded { depth, max }</code> || Recursion depth ≥ 128.
|-
| <code>PlaceholderIndexOutOfRange { idx, n }</code> || Key index ≥ <code>n</code> in non-<code>tr()</code> context (or in any <code>idx</code> field of a multi-family body / TLV entry).
|-
| <code>PathDepthExceeded { got, max }</code> || Path depth exceeds the `MAX_PATH_COMPONENTS = 15` cap. Encoder-side: the 4-bit depth field cannot represent a depth above 15, so a conformant encoder raises this before serialization; a decoder reading that field can never observe an out-of-range depth (§"origin-path-encoding"). Likewise <code>KeyCountOutOfRange</code>, <code>AltCountOutOfRange</code>, and <code>ChunkCountOutOfRange</code> guard <code>x−1</code>-coded fields whose wire range is already bounded, so they too are encoder-side checks.
|-
| <code>KGreaterThanN { k, n }</code> || Multi-family or Thresh body decoded with <code>k > n</code>.
|-
| <code>TlvOrderingViolation { prev, current }</code> || TLV entries in non-ascending tag order.
|-
| <code>ChunkSetIdMismatch { expected, derived }</code> || After reassembling a chunked payload, the chunk-set-id declared by the chunks doesn't match the SHA-256-derived id of the reassembled payload.
|}

====Decoder canonical-form validators====

Beyond the structural errors above, a conformant decoder enforces the following canonical-form rules on a decoded payload. They are additive acceptance rules — a good-faith encoder never violates them — and the reference implementation runs them in <code>crates/md-codec/src/validate.rs</code>. Cross-implementations MUST apply equivalent checks so the accepted set matches.

{| class="wikitable"
! Rule (error variant) !! Trigger
|-
| <code>PlaceholderNotReferenced { idx, n }</code> || Some <code>@i</code> with <code>0 ≤ i < n</code> never appears in the tree.
|-
| <code>PlaceholderFirstOccurrenceOutOfOrder { expected_first, got_first }</code> || The first occurrences (pre-order) of distinct placeholder indices are not in ascending order <code>@0, @1, @2, …</code>.
|-
| <code>MultipathAltCountMismatch { expected, got }</code> || The shared use-site multipath and any per-<code>@N</code> override multipath groups do not all share the same alternative count. (A <code>None</code>-multipath entry is a legal divergent structure and is skipped, not rejected.)
|-
| <code>BaselineUseSiteOverride { idx }</code> || A <code>UseSitePathOverrides</code> entry keyed on <code>@0</code> — the baseline cannot be overridden.
|-
| <code>RedundantUseSiteOverride { idx }</code> || A <code>UseSitePathOverrides</code> entry whose path equals the baseline — a redundant (non-canonical) override.
|-
| <code>ForbiddenTapTreeLeaf { tag }</code> || A tap-script leaf whose tag is in the forbidden set <code>{wpkh, tr, wsh, sh, pkh, multi, sortedmulti}</code> — none of these are BIP-342 tapscript leaves (use <code>multi_a</code> / <code>sortedmulti_a</code> inside a tap leaf).
|-
| <code>MissingExplicitOrigin { idx }</code> || A non-canonical wrapper (§"Elided origins and canonical-default paths") with an elided (depth-0) origin for some <code>@N</code> and no explicit origin supplied via the path declaration or an <code>OriginPathOverrides</code> entry.
|-
| <code>InvalidXpubBytes { idx }</code> || A <code>Pubkeys</code> TLV entry whose 33-byte compressed-pubkey field (bytes 32..65) does not parse as a valid secp256k1 point. (The 32-byte chain-code prefix is unvalidated.)
|-
| <code>OverrideOrderViolation { prev, current }</code> || Sparse-TLV <code>(idx, …)</code> entries not in strictly-ascending <code>idx</code> order.
|-
| <code>EmptyTlvEntry { tag }</code> || A present sparse TLV that carries no <code>(idx, value)</code> pairs (encoders MUST omit empty TLVs).
|}

===Decoder reporting===

For every decode attempt, decoders SHOULD report:

{| class="wikitable"
! Field !! Values !! Notes
|-
| Outcome || clean / substitution-corrected / failed || Recommended
|-
| Errors corrected || integer 0–N, with positions || Recommended when applicable
|-
| Correction method || which technique succeeded || Recommended
|-
| Verification status || which post-decode checks passed || Recommended (chunk-set-identifier check for multi-chunk decodes; seed-derived xpub match if performed)
|}

'''Confidence tiers are informative and not yet implemented.''' A future revision MAY add a confidence ladder (e.g. Confirmed / High / Probabilistic / Failed), where "Confirmed" would require ALL of: BCH decode succeeded with at most 4 substitutions corrected, chunk-set identifier verified (if multi-chunk), every <code>@i</code> matched the user's seeds at the recovered paths, and explicit user confirmation of the recovered structure; lower tiers would carry qualifiers identifying which guarantees did not hold. The reference decoder does not currently report confidence tiers, nor the <code>erasure-corrected</code> / <code>structure-aided</code> outcomes (they depend on the future erasure and guided-recovery work — FOLLOWUP <code>impl-confidence-tier-reporting-md-mk</code>).

===Guided recovery===

A guided recovery flow is '''RECOMMENDED''' (SHOULD) for an MD tool, but it is '''not yet implemented''' by the reference implementation, which performs BCH substitution-error correction only. The flow described here is '''informative''' — a design sketch for future work (FOLLOWUP <code>impl-guided-recovery-md-mk</code>, with its erasure-decoding dependency <code>impl-bch-erasure-decoding-md-mk</code>). When implemented it combines BCH ECC, erasure decoding, user-supplied structural knowledge, and seed-derived xpub verification to recover damaged backups.

When implemented, the flow would proceed through these stages, in order:

# '''Damage assessment.''' Accept the user's transcribed string(s). Display per-position character status. Allow user to mark positions as unreadable (erasures).
# '''Standard decode.''' Attempt BCH decoding with no user input. If successful, report and stop.
# '''Erasure-aware decode.''' If standard decode fails and erasures are marked, attempt erasure decoding (up to 8 erasures per string). If successful, report and stop.
# '''Structure elicitation.''' If decoding still fails, prompt the user for structural information they remember about the policy: wallet kind, key count, threshold, derivation path, timelock values, chunk-set identifier (if separately stamped).
# '''Constrained candidate search.''' Encode the user's structural assertions as a partial bytecode template. Enumerate candidate codewords within an extended Hamming radius (up to ~12) that decode to valid MD bytecode AND match the user's assertions.
# '''Candidate verification.''' For each surviving candidate, derive xpubs from available seeds at the candidate's declared paths, verify they map to the expected placeholders, verify the chunk-set identifier if multi-chunk, and reject candidates failing any check.
# '''Optional blockchain verification.''' With explicit user consent, derive the candidate's first N receive addresses and check on-chain history. Disclose privacy implications before this step.
# '''Result presentation.''' Display the recovered wallet policy in BIP 388 form, the Policy ID, derived xpubs, and the confidence level per "Decoder reporting".

A tool that implements the optional blockchain-verification stage MUST disclose privacy implications before any blockchain query, SHOULD default to offline operation, and MUST NOT transmit recovered policy material to external services without explicit user consent.

==Rationale==

===Why a new format?===

Existing engravable formats (BIP 39, codex32) target seeds (uniformly random fixed-length entropy). Neither has framing for arbitrary structured data, and neither encodes wallet structure. Bytewords / UR encodes descriptors but with weak (CRC32) error correction and verbose output. <code>descriptor-codec</code> compactly encodes descriptors but produces raw bytes designed for QR/NFC, not engraving. No existing format combines a compact descriptor encoding with strong BCH error correction in a hand-transcribable form. MD fills this gap.

===Why codex32-derived encoding?===

Codex32 (BIP 93) is purpose-built for hand-transcribed bitcoin secrets. Its bech32 alphabet excludes visually confusable characters; its BCH polynomials provide strong error correction with mathematically guaranteed bounds; reference implementations exist; the encoding scheme is well-reviewed.

However, codex32's HRP is fixed to <code>ms</code> and its header structure is hard-coded for BIP 32 master seeds (Shamir threshold and identifier fields). Codex32 has no extensibility mechanism for non-seed payloads. MD therefore reuses codex32's '''cryptographic primitives''' (alphabet, BCH polynomials) but defines its own HRP and header structure, treating codex32 as a building block rather than a host format. This is consistent with how BIP 350 (bech32m) reused BIP 173's primitives with a different generator constant.

===Why a new HRP?===

A new HRP (<code>md</code>) is required because:
* Codex32's <code>ms</code> HRP cannot be reused without breaking codex32's seed-payload semantics.
* The bech32 checksum is computed over the HRP, providing domain separation: a damaged MD string cannot be misinterpreted as a bech32 address or codex32 seed share.
* The HRP serves as format self-identification for human readers and parsers.

The two-character HRP <code>md</code> was chosen as a compact, readable abbreviation of "Mnemonic Descriptor". It was verified clean against the SLIP-0173 registry, Lightning HRPs, Liquid sidechain HRPs, Codex32 (<code>ms</code>), Nostr NIP-19 HRPs, and Cosmos chain HRPs prior to adoption.

===Why new target constants?===

The target residue constant <code>T_REGULAR</code> is derived NUMS-style ("Nothing Up My Sleeve") as a truncation of <code>SHA-256("shibbolethnums")</code> to the most significant 65 bits, interpreting the hash as a big-endian 256-bit integer. (MD has only the regular code; the long code was removed, so no <code>T_LONG</code> is defined.)

The string <code>shibbolethnums</code> combines this proposal's working name during early development with the conventional <code>nums</code> suffix used in cryptographic constructions to indicate that the value was chosen via a public hash and not through opaque selection. The string itself is the audit trail: any reader can recompute the SHA-256 and verify that the constant follows from it.

We chose a new constant rather than reusing BIP 93's <code>MS32_CONST</code> value for two reasons. First, although the HRP-mixing recipe (BIP 173 <code>hrp_expand</code>) produces residues that differ between any two HRPs sharing this polynomial, picking a distinct target constant provides residue-level separation as well: damage that maps an MD string toward codex32-style validity is statistically prevented by the combination. Second, signaling matters — reusing codex32's specific target constant verbatim would invite the misreading that MD is "codex32 with a different HRP" rather than a distinct format that borrows codex32's polynomial.

The constant is reproducible by any SHA-256 implementation:

<source lang="python">
import hashlib
h = hashlib.sha256(b"shibbolethnums").digest()
T_REGULAR = int.from_bytes(h, 'big') >> (256 - 65)  # = 0x0815c07747a3392e7
</source>

===Why descriptor-codec for the bytecode?===

<code>descriptor-codec</code> is a public-domain (CC0-1.0) Rust library that encodes BIP 380 output descriptors using a compact tag-based format with claimed 30–40% size reduction relative to plaintext. Its tag table covers all miniscript fragments and produces deterministic round-tripping bytecode. MD adopts the same tag-based approach and extends it with BIP 388 wallet-policy framing (<code>@i</code> placeholders) and bit-aligned origin / use-site path declarations. MD's v0.30 tag table is its own 6-bit primary tag space (§"Tag table"; authoritative source <code>crates/md-codec/src/tag.rs</code>) — it does not carry a path dictionary (§"origin-path-encoding") and is not byte-compatible with descriptor-codec's byte-aligned tags.

This design choice means: (a) MD does not invent a new bytecode for descriptors that are already correctly handled by an existing public-domain implementation; (b) implementations of MD that wish to also handle inline-key descriptors (a v1+ extension) can do so by adopting the existing reserved tags; (c) the MD extensions MAY be upstreamed into <code>descriptor-codec</code> if the maintainer accepts.

===Why the BIP 388 placeholder framing instead of inline keys?===

The placeholder framing has three advantages over inline keys:

# '''Compactness.''' Each <code>@i</code> reference encodes as an inline <code>key_index</code> field of just <code>kiw = ⌈log₂(n)⌉</code> bits (0–5 bits for up to 32 keys, §"Key references"), versus the ~65-byte on-wire xpub an inline key would need. For a 6-key policy this saves hundreds of bytes of bytecode — the difference between fitting one engraved plate and fitting many.
# '''Separation of structure from key material.''' The Template Card contains zero key material in v0; it can be backed up independently of seeds and xpub cards. Loss or compromise of a Template Card does not compromise key secrecy.
# '''Standard alignment.''' BIP 388 already defines the placeholder framing for hardware-signer wallet-policy registration. Aligning MD's bytecode with BIP 388's framing minimizes work for wallets that already produce BIP 388 wallet policies.

===Why is guided recovery recommended rather than mandated?===

The format's robustness story has two layers: BCH substitution-error correction (always present, and implemented) and structure-aware recovery (a design sketch — §"Guided recovery"). An earlier draft made guided recovery a conformance MUST, but the reference implementation does not yet provide it, so a MUST would render the reference non-conformant with its own spec. Guided recovery is therefore RECOMMENDED (SHOULD) and described as future work. If adopted broadly it would give MD tools consistent recovery semantics so users with damaged backups are not at the mercy of which tool they happen to use. See FOLLOWUPs <code>impl-guided-recovery-md-mk</code> and <code>impl-bch-erasure-decoding-md-mk</code>.

===Why no compression?===

The format already provides large implicit compression via the placeholder mechanism and tag-based encoding (~40× compression on key material vs inline xpubs; ~10× on operator names vs plaintext). For payload sizes typical of bitcoin wallet policies (≤ 60 bytes), generic compression (LZ-family) yields 5–20% additional savings — offset by dictionary overhead, decompressor complexity, and increased attack surface.

Hardware signers parsing MD-encoded policies (Coldcard, BitBox, Jade, Ledger) have memory and code-size constraints that favor direct opcode interpretation over compressed input. The chunking scheme handles arbitrary lengths, so compression's primary benefit (avoiding chunk boundaries) is moot.

If a future revision identifies compression as worth adding, it should be: (a) a dictionary of common timelock values; (b) an n-of-n implicit-thresh opcode for long <code>and_v</code> chains. Generic LZ on bytecode is not recommended.

===Why no built-in encryption?===

The Template Card contains no key material in v0; it encodes wallet structure. A finder of a Template Card learns the spending policy (e.g., timelock periods, threshold counts, the existence of cosigners) but cannot derive any private keys without also obtaining the user's seed(s).

Encrypting the Template Card is technically straightforward but introduces a new failure mode: loss of the encryption key separate from loss of the seed. Since the Template Card is already useless without the seed for actual fund recovery, the privacy gain from encryption (concealing wallet ''structure'') trades against the recovery risk (now requiring two independent secrets).

A future revision MAY define an optional encrypted Template Card variant. v0 does not include one.

===Why mandatory chunk-set identifier in chunked cards?===

Without per-chunk-set identifiers, a user with multiple wallets risks mixing chunks from different Template Cards during reassembly. The 20-bit identifier provides ~1-in-1M discrimination against accidental cross-wallet contamination, and because every chunk header carries the same CSI, mismatched chunks are rejected before any payload reassembly is attempted.

The 20-bit value is normatively derived from the encoding's <code>Md1EncodingId</code> (see §"Header") rather than drawn from a CSPRNG. This serves two purposes. First, it makes md1 bit-reproducible: two conforming encoders given the same canonical bytecode produce identical Template Card strings down to the wire bits, which lets downstream toolchains (engraving toolkits, regression-pinned vector corpora) SHA-pin md1 outputs without flake. Second, the deterministic binding doubles as the cross-chunk integrity check: decoders re-derive the CSI from the reassembled payload's <code>Md1EncodingId</code> and reject if it differs from the wire CSI carried in chunk headers. The v0.30 wire format does NOT carry a separate cross-chunk hash field — the CSI derivation IS the integrity check, and a non-conforming encoder that drew a random CSI value would produce strings unreadable by conforming decoders, so the determinism contract is self-enforcing.

For single-string Template Cards, no chunk-set identifier is needed because there are no chunks to confuse.

==Frequently Asked Questions==

===Why does MD warn on legacy P2SH multisig?===

BIP 388 admits six top-level wallet-policy shapes — <code>pkh(KEY)</code>, <code>wpkh(KEY)</code>, <code>sh(wpkh(KEY))</code>, <code>wsh(SCRIPT)</code>, <code>sh(wsh(SCRIPT))</code>, <code>tr(KEY[, TREE])</code> — plus legacy <code>sh(multi(...))</code> / <code>sh(sortedmulti(...))</code>. MD '''decodes''' all of them (recovery-first; §"Top-level descriptor scope"), but its encoder emits a warn-only advisory for legacy P2SH multisig and treats <code>pkh</code> as low marginal value. The reasons:

# '''Address-prefix ambiguity is a recovery footgun.''' Both <code>sh(multi(K, ...))</code> (legacy P2SH multisig, 2014–2017 era) and <code>sh(wsh(...))</code> (BIP 48/1' modern nested-segwit multisig) produce <code>3...</code> addresses. A user cannot disambiguate them from an address alone; engraving the wrong type derives the wrong addresses on recovery. The encode-time advisory surfaces this the moment a legacy card is minted, while the decoder still reads such a card so an already-engraved backup is never stranded.
# '''Engravable steel backup adds little for legacy single-sig.''' BIP 39 seed words alone reconstruct a <code>pkh(KEY)</code> wallet; the policy template adds no recovery information. So <code>pkh</code> is fully supported (and ships in the corpus) but the encoder emits no advisory — the value proposition simply does not apply.
# '''Little new pre-segwit deployment.''' Modern hardware wallets emit post-segwit forms by default; realistic users engraving 2015-era P2SH multisig are few.

This is a deliberate '''encode-time''' safety signal, not a decode-time refusal: a spec-conforming recovery tool reads every legitimately-engraved card, and refusing to decode a legacy form would strand funds.

===Why is multi-leaf TapTree deferred (vs excluded)?===

(Historical context — v0.4 deferral rationale.) <code>tr(KEY, TREE)</code> with multi-leaf TapTree (BIP 388 §"Taproot tree") is a substantive feature requiring its own design pass: TapTree depth/balancing rules, leaf-wrapper subset re-evaluation (Coldcard tap-leaf subset is currently restrictive), per-leaf miniscript context validation. Deferring to a future MD revision (v0.5+) keeps the v0.4 release focused. Unlike the legacy exclusions above, multi-leaf TapTree IS planned admission.

===Why does v0.5 admit multi-leaf TapTree?===

The v0.4 deferral was scope-driven, not design-driven. Multi-leaf TapTree was always a planned admission target; v0.5 ships it because:

# The BIP 388 modern-segwit surface (closed at v0.4 with <code>wpkh</code>, <code>sh(wpkh)</code>, <code>sh(wsh)</code>) is now stable, freeing engineering bandwidth for the taproot tree work.
# The peek-before-recurse + depth-gate hardening pattern from v0.4's <code>sh(...)</code> restriction matrix transfers directly to <code>TapTree</code>'s recursive framing — the security review surface is small.
# BIP 341's <code>TAPROOT_CONTROL_MAX_NODE_COUNT = 128</code> provides an upstream-defined ceiling that requires no MD-specific tightening, simplifying the spec.
# rust-miniscript's <code>TapTree::leaves()</code> + <code>TapTree::combine</code> APIs make the encoder/decoder a thin shim over upstream's depth-aware tree representation.

v0.5 does NOT broaden the per-leaf miniscript subset — each leaf is admissible on the same terms as v0.4.x's single-leaf <code>tr(KEY, leaf)</code> admits. The <code>validate_tap_leaf_subset</code> gate is unchanged.

===Why is <code>bare(SCRIPT)</code> rejected?===

BIP 388 itself excludes <code>bare(SCRIPT)</code> (pre-2014 raw script output type, no address). MD inherits this exclusion.

===Why no inline xpubs (foreign keys)?===

MD's <code>@i</code> placeholder framing assumes named keys provided separately at recovery time (BIP 388 wallet-policy structure). Inline xpubs (descriptor-codec reserved tags <code>0x24</code>–<code>0x31</code>) would change the recovery model: the engraved card would carry key material, defeating the steel-engravable backup form factor's value (key material is in the seeds, not the engraved card).

===What about <code>tr(KEY)</code> single-sig taproot?===

Single-key taproot (<code>tr(KEY)</code>) and single-leaf taproot (<code>tr(KEY, single-leaf-script)</code>) are both supported and have been since v0.2. As of v0.5, these are degenerate cases of the full multi-leaf admission: single-leaf is simply a tree of depth zero (no <code>TapTree</code> inner node), and keypath-only is an absent script-tree position. The bytecode encoding for both forms is UNCHANGED from v0.4.x — v0.5 is wire-additive, not wire-breaking, for these cases.

===Why is the HRP <code>md</code> rather than something more descriptive?===

Matches the 2-character convention of BIP 93's <code>ms</code> HRP for codex32. Shorter HRPs leave more capacity in the BCH-bounded data part for policy bytecode. The earlier <code>wdm</code> HRP was renamed to <code>md</code> at v0.3.0 — see CHANGELOG.

==Backwards Compatibility==

MD is a new format; there is no prior version to be compatible with.

MD does not conflict with existing standards:

* '''BIP 39 / SLIP 39 / BIP 93 (codex32):''' MD uses a different HRP (<code>md</code> vs <code>ms</code>), so an MD string is never confused with a codex32 seed share. The bech32 checksums are computed over the HRP plus data, providing cryptographic domain separation.
* '''BIP 173 / BIP 350 (bech32 / bech32m addresses):''' MD uses neither <code>bc</code>/<code>tb</code>/<code>bcrt</code> HRPs nor the bech32m generator constant; addresses cannot be confused with MD strings.
* '''BIP 380 (output descriptors):''' BIP 380 descriptors do not contain the <code>@</code> character, so a BIP 380 descriptor cannot be confused with a BIP 388 wallet policy, and neither can be confused with MD-encoded bytecode (which is binary, not a descriptor string).
* '''BIP 388 (wallet policies):''' MD ''encodes'' BIP 388 wallet policies. Round-trip with BIP 388 canonical form is a stated invariant.

MD v0 readers MUST reject MD strings with newer format-version bytes (loud failure; recommend the user obtain a newer MD tool). v1+ readers MUST accept v0 strings (graceful upgrade).

'''Wire-format breaks on the v0.x evolution path.''' Three breaks shape the v0.30 wire format (historical context):

* '''v0.x ≤ 0.9 → v0.10 (path-divergence support).''' v0.x ≤ 0.9 lossily flattened policies with divergent per-<code>@N</code> origin paths to a single shared path, so <code>decode(encode(p))</code> could differ from <code>p</code> for any policy where cosigners derived xpubs from different paths. v0.10 closed that bug by reclaiming bit 3 of the byte-aligned bytecode header as a divergent-paths flag and adding a per-<code>@N</code> path block. Pre-v0.10 decoders rejected v0.10 divergent-paths encodings cleanly via <code>Error::ReservedBitsSet</code>.
* '''v0.x ≤ 0.10 → v0.11 (bit-packed wire-format reset).''' v0.11 replaced the byte-aligned bytecode framing (1-byte header, 1-byte path-decl tags, byte-aligned operator tags) with a packed 5-bit bit stream, eliminating per-section framing tags entirely; fingerprints, xpubs, and per-<code>@N</code> overrides moved into the §"TLV section". The path-divergence fix from v0.10 was preserved (signaled by header bit 4 directly, with no framing tag); see §"Origin path declaration". v0.x ≤ 0.10 decoders could not read v0.11 encodings, and vice versa; the change was a clean break with no compat layer.
* '''v0.x → v0.30 (wire-format redesign).''' v0.30 widens the bytecode primary tag space from 5-bit to 6-bit (5 hash/literal operators promoted to primary), widens the header version field from 3-bit to 4-bit, relocates the chunked-flag to bit 0 of the first 5-bit symbol for in-band auto-dispatch, packs multi-family children as raw kiw-bit indices (no per-child tags), retires the <code>tr()</code> NUMS sentinel in favor of an explicit <code>is_nums</code> flag (restoring <code>kiw = ⌈log₂(n)⌉</code>), and refines the decoder error taxonomy. v0.x payloads fed to a v0.30 decoder raise <code>Error::WireVersionMismatch</code> cleanly per the auto-dispatch trace in §"Auto-dispatch and safe rejection". This is a clean break with no compat layer.

Users who computed PolicyIds on divergent-path policies under v0.x ≤ 0.9 SHOULD re-engrave under v0.10+. Users who recovered policies from v0.x ≤ 0.29 Template Cards SHOULD re-engrave under v0.30; v0.30 decoders cannot read pre-v0.30 encodings.

==Test Vectors==

The v0.30 reference test corpus is defined by <code>crates/md-codec/src/test_vectors.rs::MANIFEST</code> — the single source of truth — and materialized to files under <code>crates/md-codec/tests/vectors/</code> by the <code>md vectors --out &lt;dir&gt;</code> subcommand. Each <code>MANIFEST</code> entry is a <code>Vector</code> struct (<code>name</code>, <code>template</code>, <code>keys</code>, <code>fingerprints</code>, <code>force_chunked</code>, and — added for non-canonical shapes that require an explicit origin — an optional <code>path</code> field). Each vector materializes as '''four''' plain-text files sharing a common stem <code>{name}</code>:

{| class="wikitable"
! File !! Contents
|-
| <code>{name}.template</code> || The input BIP 388 wallet-policy template (e.g., <code>wsh(multi(2,@0/<0;1>/*,@1/<0;1>/*))</code>).
|-
| <code>{name}.descriptor.json</code> || The post-decode AST: a JSON serialization of the <code>Descriptor</code> struct (n, path_decl, use_site_path, tree, tlv).
|-
| <code>{name}.phrase.txt</code> || The md1 string produced by encoding the template (BCH-checksummed codex32 output).
|-
| <code>{name}.bytes.hex</code> || The raw bit-packed payload bytes (hex), pre-codex32-wrap. Used for byte-level cross-implementation checks.
|}

The <code>md vectors --out</code> runner enumerates <code>MANIFEST</code> and writes the four files per vector. For a <code>force_chunked</code> vector, the <code>{name}.phrase.txt</code> file carries an extra leading <code>chunk-set-id: 0x…</code> line before the per-chunk strings (each chunk on its own line). Conformance tests round-trip each vector: <code>encode(template) == phrase</code> and <code>decode(phrase) == descriptor</code>. Independent implementations SHOULD verify against the committed file tuples for the MD version they target.

===v0.30 corpus===

The committed v0.30 corpus carries 10 vectors:

{| class="wikitable"
! Name !! Template !! md1 string
|-
| <code>wpkh_basic</code> || <code>wpkh(@0/<0;1>/*)</code> || <code>md1yqpqqxqq8xtwhw4xwn4qh</code>
