The corpus exercises all top-level descriptor types in MD's admit set, multi-family operators (multi, sortedmulti), the Fingerprints TLV, divergent use-site-path overrides, and the chunked envelope dispatch path. Negative-vector coverage lives in unit tests (<code>crates/md-codec/src/*</code>) and integration tests (<code>crates/md-codec/tests/*</code>) rather than the file-tuple corpus.

===Reference vector walkthroughs===

The §"Bit-layout example" and §"Bit-layout examples" sections above show six v0.30 encodings bit-by-bit. The bytecode hex strings in those walkthroughs are reproducible via the reference CLI: <code>md encode &lt;template&gt; --path &lt;origin-path&gt; &lt;flags&gt;</code> followed by <code>md bytecode &lt;phrase&gt;</code>.

The four committed corpus vectors closest in shape to the bit-layout examples are:

* <code>wsh_multi_2of2</code> — same template family as the §"Bit-layout example" §1, differs in origin path (<code>m</code> vs <code>m/48'/0'/0'/2'</code>; corpus minimizes per-vector path cost).
* <code>wsh_with_fingerprints</code> — same template + TLV family as §"Bit-layout example" §2.
* <code>tr_keyonly</code> — same template family as §"Bit-layout examples" §1 (keypath-only tr).
* <code>wsh_multi_2of3</code> — exercises the multi-family raw-index-packing wire shape at <code>n = 3, kiw = 2</code>.

===Regeneration===

The committed corpus is regenerated by running <code>md vectors --out crates/md-codec/tests/vectors</code>, which rewrites the four-file tuples from a fresh encode pass of <code>src/test_vectors.rs::MANIFEST</code> and pins the BCH checksums. Conformance test runs (the default <code>cargo test</code>) compare the committed bytes against the live encoder output and fail on drift.

